# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guggenheim-fellowship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The son of an Irish American mother and a Civil War–veteran Italian American father, Smith was born and raised on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, New York City, near the Brooklyn Bridge.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He resided in that neighborhood for his entire life.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Although Smith remained personally untarnished by corruption, he—like many other New York Democrats—was linked to the notorious Tammany Hall political machine that controlled New York City politics during his era.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith served in the New York State Assembly from 1904 to 1915 and was the speaker of the Assembly in 1913.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He also served as the sheriff of New York County from 1916 to 1917.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He was first elected governor in 1918, lost his 1920 bid for re-election, and was elected again in 1922, 1924, and 1926.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was the foremost urban leader of the efficiency movement in the U.S. and was noted for achieving a wide range of reforms as governor.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was the first Catholic to be the nominee for the U.S. presidency of a major party.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His 1928 presidential candidacy mobilized both Catholic and anti-Catholic voters.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Many Protestants, particularly German Lutherans and Southern Baptists, feared his candidacy, believing that the pope in Rome would dictate his policies.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was also a committed "wet" (i.e., an opponent of Prohibition); as governor he had repealed New York State's prohibition law.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith attracted voters who wanted beer, wine, and liquor and did not like dealing with criminal bootleggers, along with voters who were outraged that new criminal gangs had taken over the streets in most large and medium-sized cities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Hoover, who was the incumbent Republican secretary of commerce, was aided by national prosperity, the absence of American involvement in war, and anti-Catholicism, and he defeated Smith in a landslide in 1928.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith then entered business in New York City, and became involved in the construction and promotion of the Empire State Building.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He sought the 1932 Democratic presidential nomination, but was defeated by Franklin D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Roosevelt, his former ally and successor as governor.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] During the Roosevelt presidency, Smith became an increasingly vocal opponent of Roosevelt's New Deal.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was born at 174 South Street and raised in the Fourth Ward on the Lower East Side of Manhattan in 1873; he resided there for his entire life.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His mother, Catherine (née Mulvihill), was the daughter of Maria Marsh and Thomas Mulvihill, who were immigrants from County Westmeath, Ireland.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His father, baptised Joseph Alfred Smith in 1839, was the son of Emanuel Smith, an Italian *marinaro* (sailor).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The elder Alfred Smith (Anglicized name for Alfredo Emanuele Ferraro) was the son of Italian and German immigrants.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He served with the 11th New York Fire Zouaves in the opening months of the Civil War.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith grew up with his family struggling financially in the Gilded Age; New York City matured and completed major infrastructure projects.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The Brooklyn Bridge was being constructed nearby.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] "The Brooklyn Bridge and I grew up together", Smith would later recall.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His four grandparents were of ethnic German, Irish as well as Italian ancestry, but Smith identified more with the Irish-American community and became its leading spokesman in the 1920s.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His father Alfred owned a small trucking firm, but died when Smith was 13.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] James parochial school to help support the family, and worked at a fish market for seven years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Prior to dropping out of school, he served as an altar boy, and was strongly influenced by the Catholic priests he worked with.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He never attended high school or college, and claimed he learned about people by studying them at the Fulton Fish Market, where he worked for $12 per week.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His acting skills made him a success on the amateur theater circuit.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He became widely known, and developed the smooth oratorical style that characterized his political career.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In his political career, Smith built on his working-class beginnings, identifying himself with immigrants and campaigning as a man of the people.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Although indebted to the Tammany Hall political machine (and particularly to its boss, "Silent" Charlie Murphy), he remained untarnished by corruption and worked for the passage of progressive legislation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] It was during his early unofficial jobs with Tammany Hall that he gained renown as an orator.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith's first political job was in 1895, as an investigator in the office of the Commissioner of Jurors as appointed by Tammany Hall.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] A “New Era Progressive”, Smith advocated local government funded facilities and services such as hospitals, parks and schools in poor and working-class areas.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Speaking of the role of the state in 1927, Smith said: "The State is a living force.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] It must have the ability to clothe itself with human understanding of the daily, living needs of those whom it is created to serve." However, Smith envisioned a progressive vision based on state and local intervention, and decentralizing power to specific locales and communities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He was ambivalent with regard to federal economic intervention, which eventually led him to oppose the New Deal legislation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was first elected to the New York State Assembly (New York Co., 2nd D.) in 1904, and was repeatedly elected to office, serving through 1915.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] After being approached by Frances Perkins, an activist, to improve labor practices, Smith sought to improve the conditions of factory workers.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith served as vice chairman of the state commission appointed to investigate factory conditions after 146 workers died in the 1911 Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Meeting the families of the deceased Triangle factory workers left a strong impression on him.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Wagner, Smith crusaded against dangerous and unhealthy workplace conditions and championed corrective legislation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The Commission, chaired by State Senator Robert F.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Wagner, held a series of widely publicized investigations around the state, interviewing 222 witnesses and taking 3,500 pages of testimony.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] They hired field agents to do on-site inspections of factories.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Starting with the issue of fire safety, they studied broader issues of the risks of injury in the factory environment.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Their findings led to thirty-eight new laws regulating labor in New York State, and gave each of them a reputation as leading progressive reformers working on behalf of the working class.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In the process, they changed Tammany's reputation from mere corruption to progressive endeavors to help the workers.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] New York City's Fire Chief John Kenlon told the investigators that his department had identified more than 200 factories where conditions resulted in risk of a fire like that at the Triangle Factory.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In the years from 1911 to 1913, sixty of the sixty-four new laws recommended by the Commission were legislated with the support of Governor William Sulzer.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1911, the Democrats obtained a majority of seats in the State Assembly, and Smith became Majority Leader and Chairman of the Committee on Ways and Means.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The following year, following the loss of the majority, he became the Minority Leader.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] When the Democrats reclaimed the majority after the next election, he was elected Speaker for the 1913 session.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He became Minority Leader again in 1914 and 1915.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In November 1915, he was elected Sheriff of New York County, New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] By now he was a leader of the Progressive movement in New York City and state.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His campaign manager and top aide was Belle Moskowitz, a daughter of Jewish immigrants.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] After serving in the patronage-rich job of sheriff of New York County beginning in 1916, Smith was elected governor of New York in 1918 with the help of Tammany Boss Charles F.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Farley, who brought Smith the upstate vote.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1919, Smith gave the famous speech "A man as low and mean as I can picture", making a drastic break with publisher William Randolph Hearst.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Hearst, known for his notoriously sensationalist and largely left-wing position in the state Democratic Party, was the leader of its populist wing in the city.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He had combined with Tammany Hall in electing the local administration, and had attacked Smith for starving children by not reducing the cost of milk.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith lost his bid for re-election in the 1920 New York gubernatorial election, but was again elected governor in 1922, 1924 and 1926, with Farley managing his campaign.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In his 1922 re-election, he embraced his position as an anti-prohibitionist.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith offered alcohol to guests at the Executive Mansion in Albany, and repealed the state's Prohibition enforcement statute, the Mullan-Gage law.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] As governor, Smith became known nationally as a progressive who sought to make government more efficient and more effective in meeting social needs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith's assistant Robert Moses built the nation's first state park system and reformed the civil service, later gaining appointment as Secretary of State of New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] During Smith's time in office, New York strengthened laws governing workers' compensation, women's pensions and children and women's labor with the help of Frances Perkins, soon to be President Franklin D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1924, Smith unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for president, advancing the cause of civil liberty by decrying lynching and racial violence.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The party was hopelessly split between the two.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] An increasingly chaotic convention balloted 100 times before both men accepted that neither would be able to win the required two-thirds of the votes, and so each withdrew.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] On the 103rd ballot, the exhausted party nominated the little-known candidate John W.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Davis of West Virginia, a former congressman and United States Ambassador to Great Britain who had been a dark horse presidential candidate in 1920.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Davis lost the election by a landslide to Republican incumbent Calvin Coolidge, who won in part because of the prosperous times.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Undeterred, Smith returned to fight a determined campaign for the party's nomination in 1928.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He was aided by the endorsement of Philip La Follette, son of 1924 Progressive Party presidential candidate Robert M.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] La Follette, who died in 1925 seven months after receiving 16.62 percent of the popular vote—the fifth-highest proportion for any third-party presidential candidate.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Reporter Frederick William Wile made the oft-repeated observation that Smith was defeated by "the three P's: Prohibition, Prejudice and Prosperity".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The Republican Party was still benefiting from an economic boom, as well as a failure to reapportion Congress and the electoral college following the 1920 census, which had registered a 15 percent increase in the urban population.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The party was biased toward small-town and rural areas.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Its presidential candidate Herbert Hoover, who headed the Census of 1920, did little to alter this state of affairs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Historians agree that prosperity, along with widespread anti-Catholic sentiment against Smith, made Hoover's election inevitable.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He defeated Smith by a landslide in the 1928 United States presidential election, carrying five Southern states via crossover voting by conservative white Democrats.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The fact that Smith was Catholic and the descendant of Catholic immigrants was instrumental in his loss of the election of 1928.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Historical hostilities between Protestants and Catholics had been carried by national groups to the United States by immigrants, and centuries of Protestant domination allowed myths and superstitions about Catholicism to flourish.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Long-established Protestants had viewed the waves of Catholic immigrants from Ireland, Italy and Eastern Europe since the mid-19th century with suspicion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In addition, many Protestants carried old fears related to extravagant claims of one religion against the other which dated back to the European wars of religion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] They feared that Smith would answer to the Pope rather than the United States Constitution.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Scott Farris notes that the anti-Catholicism of American society was the sole reason behind Smith's defeat, as even contemporary Prohibition activists would admit that their main problem with the Democratic candidate was his faith and not any political view.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] A Methodist newspaper in Georgia called Catholicism "a degenerate type of Christianity," while Southern Baptist newspapers ordered their readers to vote against Smith, claiming that he would close down Protestant churches, end freedom of worship and prohibit reading the Bible.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Charles Hillman Fountain, a Protestant writer, insisted that Catholics should be barred from holding any office.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Farris states that "More disturbing than the ridiculous and the dangerous was the respectable anti-Catholicism", as contemporary newspapers and Protestant churches tried to mask their anti-Catholicism as genuine concern.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Protestant activists insisted that Catholicism represents an alien culture and medieval mentality, claiming that Catholicism is incompatible with American democracy and institutions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Catholics were portrayed as reactionary despite being more centrist than mainstream American Protestant congregations at the time.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] White rural conservatives in the South also believed that Smith's close association with Tammany Hall, the Democratic machine in Manhattan, showed that he tolerated corruption in government, while they overlooked their own brands of it.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Another major controversial issue was the continuation of Prohibition, the enforcement of which was widely considered problematic.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith personally favored the relaxation or repeal of Prohibition laws because they had given rise to more criminality.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The Democratic Party split North and South on the issue, with the more rural South continuing to favor Prohibition.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] During the campaign, Smith tried to duck the issue with non-committal statements.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was an articulate proponent of good government and efficiency, as was Hoover.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith swept the entire Catholic vote, which in 1920 and 1924 had been split between the parties; he attracted millions of Catholics, generally ethnic whites, to the polls for the first time, especially women, who were first allowed to vote in 1920.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He lost important Democratic constituencies in the rural North as well as in Southern cities and suburbs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith did retain the loyalty of the Deep South, thanks in part to the appeal of his running mate, Senator Joseph Robinson from Arkansas, but lost five states of the Rim South to Hoover.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith carried the popular vote in each of America's ten most populous cities, an indication of the rising power of the urban areas and their new demographics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His campaign theme song, "The Sidewalks of New York", had little appeal among rural Americans, who also found his 'city' accent slightly foreign when heard on radio.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith narrowly lost his home state; New York's electors were biased in favor of rural upstate and largely Protestant districts.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] However, in 1928, his fellow Democrat Franklin D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Roosevelt (a Protestant of Dutch old-line stock) was elected to replace him as governor of New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Farley left Smith's camp to run Roosevelt's successful campaign for governor in 1928, and then Roosevelt's successful campaigns for the Presidency in 1932 and 1936.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Some political scientists believe that the 1928 election started a voter realignment that helped develop Roosevelt's New Deal coalition.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Lichtman notes that the sole defining issue of the election was anti-Catholicism, which radically realigned states' voting patterns.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] States that had never voted Republican after Reconstruction, such as Texas, Florida, North Carolina and Virginia, voted for Hoover, while Smith carried Massachusetts and Rhode Island—states that had never voted Democratic before save for 1912.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Lichtman further proves this by pointing out that Smith and Hoover had very similar political views save for religion and Prohibition, and yet the 1928 election had a turnout of 57%, despite previous 1920s American elections having their turnouts below 50%.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Finan (2003) says Smith is an underestimated symbol of the changing nature of American politics in the first half of the last century.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He represented the rising ambitions of urban, industrial America at a time when the hegemony of rural, agrarian America was in decline, although many states had legislatures and congressional delegations biased toward rural areas due to a lack of redistricting after censuses.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was connected to the hopes and aspirations of immigrants, especially Catholics and Jews from eastern and southern Europe.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was a devout Catholic, but his struggles against religious bigotry were often misinterpreted when he fought the religiously inspired Protestant morality imposed by prohibitionists.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The 1928 election initiated a complete voter realignment of African-Americans, who overwhelmingly supported the Republican Party prior to 1928.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Hoover sought "Southern Strategy" for the election, and sided with the segregationist lily-white Republicans at the expense of the pro-civil rights black and tans.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Prominent African Americans were removed from positions of leadership in the Republican Party and replaced with lily-white Republicans in order to appeal to the segregationist South, and Hoover's spokesmen in the South spoke of his commitment to white supremacy.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Al Smith was supportive of racial equality and appointed African Americans to the New York City school system and the New York City Civil Service Commission.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith attracted the attention of disheartened African-American voters, as he was unpopular in the South, faced prejudice as a Catholic, and had a reputation of a "spokesman for ethnic minorities in Northern cities".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] As such, Smith's candidacy, coupled with Hoover's Southern concession, initiated abandonment of loyalty to the Republicans and embrace of the Democratic Party by African-American voters.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was also known as an economic progressive, and championed progressive reforms such as a shorter workweek, workers' compensation laws, as well as health and workplace safety reforms.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Many of his reforms later inspired the New Deal, even though Smith himself came to oppose the New Deal legislation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] However, Smith said little about his economic progressivism on the 1928 campaign trail, as the public was largely supportive of the conservative economic vision that the incumbent Republican administration pursued, crediting it with the economic prosperity at the time.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith felt slighted by Roosevelt during the latter's governorship.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] They became rivals in the 1932 Democratic Party presidential primaries after Smith decided to run for the nomination against Roosevelt, the presumed favorite.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] At the convention, Smith's animosity toward Roosevelt was so great that he put aside longstanding rivalries to work with McAdoo and Hearst to block Roosevelt's nomination for several ballots.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] That coalition fell apart when Smith refused to work on finding a compromise candidate; instead, he maneuvered to become the nominee.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] After losing the nomination, Smith eventually campaigned for Roosevelt in 1932, giving a particularly important speech on behalf of the Democratic nominee at Boston on October 27 in which he "pulled out all the stops".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith became highly critical of Roosevelt's New Deal policies, which he deemed a betrayal of good-government progressive ideals and ran counter to the goal of close cooperation with business.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith joined the American Liberty League, an organization founded by conservative Democrats who disapproved of Roosevelt's New Deal measures and tried to rally public opinion against the New Deal.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] The League published pamphlets and sponsored radio programs, arguing that the New Deal was destroying personal liberty; however, the League failed to gain support in the 1934 or 1936 elections and rapidly declined in influence.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith's antipathy to Roosevelt and his policies was so great that he supported Republican presidential nominees Alf Landon in the 1936 election and Wendell Willkie in the 1940 election.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] According to Jonathan Alter, the reasons for Smith's opposition to Roosevelt's New Deal were principally personal rather than ideological.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Roosevelt wronged Smith in 1931 by opposing the proposal for an unequivocal stand for repeal of Prohibition postulated by Smith and his Northern progressive wing of the party.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Moreover, many of Smith's proposals and policies from his time as governor of New York were expanded and turned into federal legislation within the New Deal, leading Smith to believe that Roosevelt stole his ideas and was taking credit for them at his expense.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Speaking of Roosevelt in 1932, Smith proclaimed: "Frank Roosevelt just threw me out of a window." Smith later abandoned his criticism of the New Deal once Roosevelt arranged for the Reconstruction Finance Corporation to rent space in the Empire State Building, which eased Smith's financial problems.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Although personal resentment was one factor in Smith's break with Roosevelt and the New Deal, Christopher Finan (2003) argues that Smith was consistent in his beliefs and politics, suggesting that Smith always believed in social mobility, economic opportunity, religious tolerance, and individualism.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was also far less supportive of direct federal intervention, on which "he was ambivalent, even uncertain." Despite the break between the men, Smith and Eleanor Roosevelt remained close.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1936, while Smith was in Washington, D.C., making a vehement radio attack on the President, she invited him to stay at the White House.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] To avoid embarrassing the Roosevelts, he declined.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Historian Robert Slayton observes that Smith and Roosevelt did not reconcile until a brief meeting in June 1941, and he also suggests that during the early 1940s, the antipathy which Smith held toward his former ally had waned.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Upon the death of Smith's wife, Katie, in May 1944, Roosevelt sent Smith a note of personal condolence.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith's grandchildren later recalled that he was greatly touched by it.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] After the 1928 election, Smith became the president of Empire State, Inc., the corporation that built and operated the Empire State Building.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Construction for the building symbolically began on March 17, 1930, St.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Patrick's Day, per Smith's instructions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith's grandchildren cut the ribbon when the world's tallest skyscraper opened on May 1, 1931, which was May Day, an international labor celebration.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Its construction had been completed in only 13 months, a record for such a large project.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] As with the Brooklyn Bridge, which Smith had seen being built from his Lower East Side boyhood home, the Empire State Building was both a vision and an achievement that had been constructed by combining the interests of all, rather than being divided by the interests of a few.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith continued to promote the Empire State Building, which was derided as the "Empty State Building" due to a lack of tenants, in the years following its construction.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1929, Smith was awarded the Laetare Medal by the University of Notre Dame, considered the most prestigious award for American Catholics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1929 Smith was elected President of the Board of Trustees of the New York State College of Forestry at Syracuse University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Knowing his fondness for animals, in 1934 Robert Moses made Al Smith the Honorary Night Zookeeper of the newly renovated Central Park Zoo.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Though a ceremonial title, Smith was given keys to the zoo and often took guests to see the animals after hours.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith was an early and vocal critic of the Nazi regime in Germany.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He supported the Anti-Nazi boycott of 1933 and addressed a mass-meeting at Madison Square Garden against Nazism that March.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His speech was included in the 1934 anthology *Nazism: An Assault on Civilization*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1938, Smith took to the airwaves to denounce Nazi brutality in the wake of *Kristallnacht*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] His words were published in *The New York Times* article "Text of the Catholic Protest Broadcast" of November 17, 1938.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Like most New York City businessmen, Smith enthusiastically supported American military involvement in World War II.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Although he was not asked by Roosevelt to play any role in the war effort, Smith was an active and vocal proponent of FDR's attempts to amend the Neutrality Act in order to allow "Cash and Carry" sales of war equipment to be made to the British.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith spoke on behalf of the policy in October 1939, to which FDR responded directly: "Very many thanks.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] In 1939, Smith was appointed a Papal Chamberlain of the Sword and Cape, one of the highest honors which the Papacy bestowed on a layman.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Smith died at the Rockefeller Institute Hospital on October 4, 1944, of a heart attack, at the age of 70.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] He had been broken-hearted over the death of his wife from cancer five months earlier, on May 4, 1944.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] Patrick's Cathedral and is interred at Calvary Cemetery.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/alfred-e-smith] On May 6, 1900, Al Smith married Catherine Ann Dunn, with whom he had five children.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard College has independent admission, curricula, and finances separate from Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It shares sports teams with Columbia through the Columbia–Barnard Athletic Consortium, an agreement that makes Barnard the only women's college to compete in NCAA Division I athletics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard College offers Bachelor of Arts degree programs in about 50 areas of study.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In addition to Columbia, students may also pursue elements of their education at the Juilliard School, the Manhattan School of Music, and the Jewish Theological Seminary which are also based in New York City.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Its 4-acre (1.6 ha) campus is located in the Upper Manhattan neighborhood of Morningside Heights, stretching along Broadway between 116th and 120th Streets.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It is directly across from Columbia's main campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard College alumnae include leaders in science, religion, politics, the Peace Corps, medicine, law, education, communications, theater, and business.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard graduates have been recipients of Emmy, Tony, Grammy, Academy, and Peabody awards, Guggenheim Fellowships, MacArthur Fellowships, the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the National Medal of Science, and the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] From its founding in 1754 until the mid-1980s, Columbia College of Columbia University admitted only men for undergraduate study.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard College was founded in 1889 as a response to Columbia's refusal to admit women.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Classes took place in a rented brownstone at 343 Madison Avenue, where a faculty of six offered instruction to 36 students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The college was named after Frederick Augustus Porter Barnard, a deaf American educator and mathematician who later served as Columbia's president for over twenty years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] He advocated for coeducational settings and proposed in 1879 that Columbia admit women.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Columbia's Board of Trustees repeatedly rejected Barnard's suggestion, but in 1883 agreed to create a syllabus that would allow the college's students to receive degrees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The first such graduate received her bachelor's degree in 1887.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] A former student of the program, Annie Meyer, and other prominent New York women persuaded the board in 1889 to create a women's college connected to Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Men and women were evenly represented among the founding trustees of Barnard College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] When Columbia University announced in 1892 its impending move to Morningside Heights, Barnard built a new campus nearby with gifts from Mary E.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Brinckerhoff, Elizabeth Milbank Anderson and Martha Fiske.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Two of these gifts were made with several stipulations attached.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Brinckerhoff insisted that Barnard acquire land within 1,000 feet of the Columbia campus within the next four years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The Barnard trustees purchased land between 119th–120th Streets after receiving funds for that purpose in 1895.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Rich designed the Milbank, Brinckerhoff, and Fiske Halls, built in 1897–1898; these were listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The first classes at the new campus were held in 1897.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Despite Brinckerhoff's, Anderson's, and Fiske's gifts, Barnard remained in debt.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Ella Weed supervised the college in its first four years; Emily James Smith succeeded her as Barnard's first dean.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Jessica Finch is credited with coining the phrase *current events* while teaching at Barnard College in the 1890s.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The college received the three blocks south of 119th Street from Anderson in 1903.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Rich provided a master plan for the campus, but only Brooks Hall was built, being constructed between 1906 and 1908.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] None of Rich's other plans was carried out.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Students' Hall, now known as Barnard Hall, was built in 1916 to a design by Arnold Brunner.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Hewitt Hall was the last structure to be erected, in 1926–1927.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] All three buildings were listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] By the mid-20th century, Barnard had succeeded in its original goal of providing a top-tier education to women.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Between 1920 and 1974, only the much larger Hunter College and University of California, Berkeley produced more women graduates who later received doctorates.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In the 1970s, Barnard faced considerable pressure to merge with male only Columbia College, which was fiercely resisted by its president, Jacquelyn Mattfeld.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Resigned to lead the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students are able to pursue a bachelor of arts degree in about 50 areas of study.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Joint programs for the bachelor of science and other degrees exist with Columbia University, Juilliard School, and the Jewish Theological Seminary.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The liberal arts general education requirements are collectively called Foundations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Students must take two courses in the sciences (one of which must be accompanied by a laboratory course), study a single foreign language for two semesters, and take two courses in the arts/humanities as well as two in the social sciences.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In addition, students must complete at least one three-credit course in the so-called "Modes of Thinking" series, and fulfill other requirements.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Admissions to Barnard are considered "most selective" by *U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It is the most selective women's college in the nation; in 2017, Barnard had the lowest acceptance rate of the five Seven Sisters that remain single-sex in admissions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The class of 2026's admission rate was 8% of the 12,009 applicants, the lowest acceptance rate in the institution's history.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The median SAT composite score of enrolled students was 1440, with median subscores of 720 in Math and 715 in Evidence-Based Reading and Writing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In 2015, Barnard announced that it would admit transgender women who "consistently live and identify as women, regardless of the gender assigned to them at birth" and would continue to support and enroll those students who transitioned to male after they had already been admitted.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The college practices need-blind admission for domestic first-year applicants.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] News & World Report* ranked Barnard as tied at 13th of 211 U.S. liberal arts colleges overall.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard was tied for 30th for "Best Undergraduate Teaching" among U.S. liberal arts colleges by *U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] *Forbes* ranked Barnard 73rd of 500 colleges in 2023.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In 2024, *Washington Monthly* ranked Barnard 63rd among 194 liberal arts colleges in the U.S. based on its contribution to the public good, as measured by social mobility, research, and promoting public service.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] While Barnard students have access to the libraries at Columbia University, the college has always maintained a library of its own.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The Barnard Library also encompasses the Archives and Special Collections, with material that documents Barnard's history from its founding to the present day.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Among the collections are the Ntozake Shange papers.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The Barnard Zine Library is a unit of the Barnard Library and Academic Information Systems (BLAIS).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Zine collections target primarily female, default queer, intentionally of color, and gender expansive topics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In 2004, it became the first zine library in the United States to be fully cataloged in the OCLC.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It opened for circulation in 2008, and holds roughly 5,000 processed zines as of 2018.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The library supports the student-run Barnard Zine Club.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Every Barnard student is part of the Student Government Association (SGA), which elects a representative student government.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] SGA aims to facilitate the expression of opinions on matters that directly affect the Barnard community.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Student groups include theater and vocal music groups, language clubs, literary magazines, a freeform radio station called WBAR, a biweekly magazine called the *Barnard Bulletin*, Club Q, community service groups, and others.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students can join extracurricular activities or organizations at Columbia University, while Columbia University students are allowed in most, but not all, Barnard organizations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard's McIntosh Activities Council organizes various community focused events on campus, such as Big Sub and Midnight Breakfast.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] There are sub-committees focussed on cultural events (Mosaic), health and wellness (Wellness), networking (Network), event-planning (Community), and service (Action).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students participate in various sororities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard Greek Games: One of Barnard's oldest traditions, the Barnard Greek Games were first held in 1903, and occurred annually until the Columbia University protests in 1968.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Since then they have been sporadically revived.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The games consist of competitions between each graduating class at Barnard, and events have traditionally included Greek poetry recitation, dance, chariot racing, and a torch race.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Take Back the Night: Each April, Barnard and Columbia students participate in the Take Back the Night march and speak-out.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] This annual event grew out of a 1988 Seven Sisters conference.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The march grew from less than 200 participants in 1988 to more than 2,500 in 2007.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Midnight breakfast marks the beginning of finals week.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] As a highly popular event and long-standing college tradition, Midnight Breakfast is hosted by the student-run activities council, McAC (McIntosh Activities Council).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In addition to providing standard breakfast foods, each year's theme is also incorporated into the menu.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Past themes have included "I YUMM the 90s," "Grease," and "Take Me Out to the Ballgame." The event is a school-wide affair as college deans, trustees and the president serve food to about a thousand students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It takes place the night before finals begin every semester.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Big Sub: Toward the beginning of each fall semester, Barnard College supplies a 700+ feet long subway sandwich.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Students from the college can take as much of the sub as they can carry.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The sub has kosher, dairy free, vegetarian, and vegan sections.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] This event is organized by the student-run activities council, McAC.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Columbia refers to Barnard as one of its schools and an affiliated institution that is a faculty of the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Both the college and Columbia evaluate Barnard faculty for tenure; in other words, a Barnard tenured professor is a Columbia tenured professor.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard graduates receive Columbia diplomas signed by the Barnard and the Columbia presidents; both diplomas are titled *Cvratores Vniversitatis Colvmbiae* ('Trustees of Columbia University').
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] According to the university, the Barnard College degree is held to the same standard as the Columbia College degree.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Additionally, both—Barnard College and Columbia College—Columbia University diplomas are written in Latin.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard graduates are also considered members of the Columbia Alumni Association (CAA), and are eligible to receive honors such as the annual Columbia Alumni Medal.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students wear the same graduation gown as undergraduates from Columbia College, the School of Engineering and Applied Science, and the School of General Studies, and their degrees are conferred during the University Commencement ceremony.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Smith and Columbia president Seth Low worked to open Columbia classes to Barnard students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] By 1900 they could attend Columbia classes in philosophy, political science, and several scientific fields.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] That year, Barnard formalized an affiliation with the university that made available to its students the instruction and facilities of Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Franz Boas, who taught at both Columbia and Barnard in the early 1900s, was among those faculty members who reportedly found Barnard students superior to their male Columbia counterparts.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] From 1955, Columbia and Barnard students could register for the other school's classes with the permission of the instructor; from 1973 no permission was needed.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Except for Columbia College, by the 1940s, other undergraduate and graduate divisions of Columbia University admitted women.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] McGill predicted in 1970 that Barnard College and Columbia College would merge within five years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In 1973, Columbia and Barnard signed a three-year agreement to increase sharing classrooms, facilities, and housing, and cooperation in faculty appointments, which they described as "integration without assimilation"; by the mid-1970s, most Columbia dormitories were coed.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The 1973–1976 chairwoman of the board at Barnard, Eleanor Thomas Elliott, led the resistance to the takeover.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The college's marketing emphasized the Columbia relationship, however; the *Bulletin* in 1976 said that Barnard described it as identical to the one between Harvard College and Radcliffe College ("who are merged in practically everything but name at this point").
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] After Barnard rejected later merger proposals from Columbia and a one-year extension to the 1973 agreement expired, in 1977, the two schools began discussing their future relationship.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] By 1979, the relationship had so deteriorated that Barnard officials stopped attending meetings.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Because of an expected decline in enrollment, in 1980 a Columbia committee recommended that Columbia College begin admitting women without Barnard's cooperation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] A 1981 committee found that Columbia was no longer competitive with other Ivy League universities without women, and that admitting women would not affect Barnard's applicant pool.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] That year Columbia president Michael Sovern agreed for the two schools to cooperate in admitting women to Columbia, but Barnard faculty's opposition caused president Ellen Futter to reject the agreement.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] A decade of negotiations for a Columbia-Barnard merger akin to Harvard and Radcliffe had failed.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In January 1982, the two schools instead announced that Columbia College would begin admitting women in 1983, and Barnard's control over tenure for its faculty would increase; previously, a committee on which Columbia faculty outnumbered Barnard's three to two controlled the latter's tenure.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Applications to Columbia rose 56% that year, making admission more selective, and nine Barnard students transferred to Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Eight students admitted to both Columbia and Barnard chose Barnard, while 78 chose Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Within a few years, however, selectivity rose at both schools as they received more women applicants than expected.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The Columbia-Barnard affiliation continued.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] As of 2012, Barnard paid Columbia about $5 million a year under the terms of the "interoperate relationship, " which the two schools renegotiate every 15 years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Despite the affiliation, Barnard is legally and financially separate from Columbia with an independent faculty and board of trustees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] It is responsible for its own separate admissions, health, security, guidance and placement services, and has its own alumnae association.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Nonetheless, Barnard students participate in the academic, social, athletic and extracurricular life of the broader university community on a reciprocal basis.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The affiliation permits the two schools to share some academic resources; for example, only Barnard has an urban studies and dance department and only Columbia has a computer science department.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Most Columbia classes are open to Barnard students and vice versa.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students and faculty are represented in the University Senate, and student organizations such as the *Columbia Daily Spectator* are open to all students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard students play on Columbia athletics teams, including the Ivy League Consortium, and Barnard uses Columbia email, telephone, and network services.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard athletes compete in the Ivy League (NCAA Division I) through the Columbia-Barnard Athletic Consortium, which was established in 1983.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Through the arrangement, Barnard is the only women's college offering Division I athletics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] There are 15 intercollegiate teams, and students also compete at the intramural and club levels.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In the spring of 1960, Columbia University president Grayson Kirk complained to the president of Barnard that Barnard students were wearing inappropriate clothing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The garments in question were pants and Bermuda shorts.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The administration forced the student council to institute a dress code.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Students would be allowed to wear shorts and pants only at Barnard and only if the shorts were no more than two inches above the knee and the pants were not tight.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard women crossing the street to enter the Columbia campus wearing shorts or pants were required to cover themselves with a long coat.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] She was called before Barnard's student-faculty administration judicial committee, where she faced the possibility of expulsion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] A student protest included a petition signed by 300 other Barnard women, admitting that they too had broken the regulations against cohabitating.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The judicial committee reached a compromise and the student was allowed to remain in school, but was denied use of the college cafeteria and barred from all social activities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The student briefly became a focus of intense national attention.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard president Martha Peterson overruled the committee and expelled LeClair.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In February 2025, Barnard College expelled two students following their disruption of a "History of Modern Israel" class at Columbia University on January 21, 2025.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The protesters demanded the reversal of the expulsions, amnesty for students disciplined for pro-Palestinian actions, and a public meeting with college administrators.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] During the protest, a Barnard employee was physically assaulted and required hospitalization.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Barnard's faculty members Nara Milanich, professor of history, and Severin Fowles, professor of anthropology and American studies, served as mediators between the protesters and the administration.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The sit-in lasted for over six hours before an agreement was reached to disperse, with a private meeting between the protesters and administrators scheduled for the following day.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] In July, Barnard College settled its lawsuit *Students Against Antisemitism, Inc. et al v.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] The Trustees of Columbia University in the City of New York et al* which accused Barnard of not taking enough measures to combat campus antisemitism.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Graduates include academic Louise Holland (1914), author Zora Neale Hurston (1928), Grace Lee Boggs, author and political activist (1935), author Patricia Highsmith (1942), biologist Leona Zacharias, television host Ronnie Eldridge (1952), Phyllis E.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Representative Helen Gahagan (1924), author Erica Jong (1963), Helene D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Gayle, Spelman College's 11th President and former chair of the Presidential Advisory Council on HIV/AIDS (1970), Susan N.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/barnard-college] Herman, president of the American Civil Liberties Union (1968), Judith Kaye, Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals (1958), Wilma B.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Since 2009, the magazine has been owned by Bloomberg L.P. and became a monthly in June 2024.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Originally published as a resource for business managers, the magazine shifted its strategy in the 1970s and added consumers outside the business world.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] By 1975, the magazine was carrying more advertising pages annually than any other magazine in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Shepard served as editor-in-chief from 1984 until 2005, when he was chosen to be the founding dean of the CUNY Graduate School of Journalism.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Under Shepard, *Businessweek*'s readership grew to more than six million in the late 1980s.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In late 2009, Bloomberg L.P. bought the magazine—reportedly for between $2 million to $5 million plus assumption of liabilities—and renamed it *Bloomberg BusinessWeek*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] News reports published in 2019 suggest McGraw-Hill received the high end of the speculated price, at $5 million, along with the assumption of debt.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In early 2010, the magazine title was restyled as *Bloomberg Businessweek* (with a lowercase "w") as part of a redesign.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] During the following years, the bold, eclectic, playful, and memetic face of *Businessweek* was cultivated largely by *Businessweek*'s creative director Richard Turley, then Rob Vargas (from 2014), and Deputy Creative director Tracy Ma (from 2011 through 2016).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] During her time at *Businessweek*, Ma worked on over 200 issues.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] As of 2014, the magazine was losing $30 million per year, about half of the $60 million it was reported losing in 2009.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Adler resigned as editor-in-chief and was replaced by Josh Tyrangiel, who had been deputy managing editor of *Time* magazine.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2016, Bloomberg announced changes to *Businessweek*, which was losing between $20 and $30 million.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Nearly 30 Bloomberg News journalists were let go across the U.S., Europe, and Asia, and it was announced that a new version of *Bloomberg Businessweek* would launch the following year.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In addition, editor-in-chief Ellen Pollock stepped down from her position, and Washington Bureau Chief Megan Murphy was named editor-in-chief.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Megan Murphy served as editor from November 2016; until she stepped down from the role in January 2018, and Joel Weber was appointed by the editorial board in her place.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Brad Stone was appointed editor of the magazine in January 2024, when the magazine switched to publishing biweekly.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In June of the same year, the magazine became a monthly.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] On October 4, 2018, *Bloomberg Businessweek* published "The Big Hack: How China Used a Tiny Chip to Infiltrate U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Companies," an article by Jordan Robertson and Michael Riley that claimed that China had hacked dozens of technology corporations, including Amazon and Apple, by placing an extra integrated circuit on a Supermicro server motherboard during manufacturing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Pingwest, a media company founded in Silicon Valley and based in Beijing, identified the chip mentioned in the article as a balun.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] The company pointed out that its size made it impossible to implement any form of attack; it did not have the storage space required to store commands that would allow a hacker to infiltrate the hardware.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] They suggested that *Businessweek* had underestimated security standards employed by Amazon and Apple.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Bloomberg's claims have faced significant scrutiny.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] By 2 p.m. on the day of publication, Apple, Amazon, and Supermicro issued blanket denials, which Bloomberg reported.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Within the week, the United States Department of Homeland Security stated that it saw no reason to question those refutations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] The National Security Agency, as well as the Government Communications Headquarters and National Cyber Security Centre of the United Kingdom, also denied the article's claims.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2021, Bloomberg published a follow-up article that stood by its allegations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] International editions of *Businessweek* were available on newsstands in Europe and Asia until 2005, when publication of regional editions was suspended to help increase foreign readership of customized European and Asian versions of *Businessweek*'s website.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] That same year, however, the Russian edition was launched in collaboration with Rodionov Publishing House.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] At the same time, *Businessweek* partnered with InfoPro Management, a publishing and market research company based in Beirut, Lebanon, to produce the Arabic version of the magazine in 22 Arab countries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2011, *Bloomberg Businessweek* continued its international expansion and announced plans to introduce a Polish-language edition called *Bloomberg Businessweek Polska*, as well as a Chinese edition, which was relaunched in November 2011.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Also in 2011, *Bloomberg Businessweek* launched an iPad version of the magazine using Apple's subscription billing service.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] The iPad edition was the first to use this subscription method, which allows one to subscribe via an iTunes account.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] There are over 100,000 subscribers to the iPad edition of *Businessweek*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2011, *Adweek* named *Bloomberg Businessweek* as the top business magazine in the U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2012, *Bloomberg Businessweek* won the general excellence award for general-interest magazines at the National Magazine Awards.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] Also in 2012, *Bloomberg Businessweek* editor Josh Tyrangiel was named magazine editor of the year by *Ad Age*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/bloomberg-businessweek] In 2014, *Bloomberg Businessweek* won a Society of American Business Editors and Writers Best in Business award for magazines, general excellence.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Career portfolios help with a job or acceptance into higher education institutes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] A career portfolio should be personal and contain critical information.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Items that should be included include (but are not limited to) personal information, evaluations, sample work, a business portrait, and awards and acknowledgments.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Career portfolios are often kept in a simple three-ring binder or online as an electronic portfolio and updated often.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] A career portfolio is used as a marketing tool in selling oneself for personal advancement.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] In some industries, employers or admission offices commonly request a career portfolio, so it is a wise idea to have an updated one on hand.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] In the 21st century web technology has filtered its way into portfolios especially in the digital workplace job market.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] While traditional C.V. style portfolios still dominate the portfolio world it is common to back it up with a website containing personal statements, contact details, and experience.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] More and more job seekers are building personally branded websites to validate and distinguish their skills, accomplishments, and experiences.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Social websites such as LinkedIn and Twitter have become popular, as have services from websites that offer to host portfolios for clients.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] These web services provide users the tools to include all forms of digital media on their websites, including documents, images, videos, and audio files.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Resume reels and demo tapes are a type of portfolio.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] They are used by many in the arts such as musicians, actors, artists, and even journalists.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Creative Professionals also use portfolio-oriented websites as a means of presenting their work in a more professional and elegant manner.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] A typical type of portfolio is used by artists.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] An artist's portfolio consists of artwork that the artist can take to job interviews, conferences, galleries, and other networking opportunities to showcase his or her work and give others an idea of what type of genre the artist works in.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Art Portfolios, sometimes called "artfolios", can be a variety of sizes, and usually consist of approximately ten to twenty photographs of the artist's best works.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Some artists create multiple portfolios to showcase different styles and to apply for different types of jobs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] For instance, one portfolio may be mainly for doing technical illustrations and another may be for surreal painting or sculpture.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Models and actors often use electronic portfolios to showcase their careers with a digital display of their photos, biographies, and skills.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Talent portfolios can also include video.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Animators typically use demo reels, also known as "demo tapes", in place of or in addition to portfolios to demonstrate their skills to potential employers.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Demo tapes have historically been short VHS tapes, but most are now DVDs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Demo reels are normally less than two minutes in length and showcase some of the animator's best works.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Another type of industry that can use portfolios as a developmental tool is schools at various levels.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Teachers can use these portfolios as an asset to themselves and to their students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Students typically can use portfolios as a tool to select the types of work that they would like to include, reflect on the course work to make connections between the units learned, and help them learn critical thinking skills that are developed during the reflecting and selecting processes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] For teachers, however, they are able to put controls on their student's portfolios to help the students throughout the portfolio process.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Once the portfolios are completed by each student, the educators of the particular subject are able to look through each portfolio and find any areas that are commonly struggled on by the students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Once this common trouble area in a unit is found, the teacher can now figure out a new way/ adjust the assignments or teaching strategies that were used to educate the students on that particular subject area.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] The three major types of portfolios are working portfolios, display portfolios, and assessment portfolios.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Although the types are distinct in theory, they tend to overlap in practice.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/career-portfolio] Consequently, a district's program may include several different types of portfolios, serving several different purposes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university was renamed Columbia College in 1784 following the American Revolution, and in 1787 was placed under a private board of trustees headed by former students Alexander Hamilton and John Jay.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, the campus was moved to its current location and renamed Columbia University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is organized into 17 schools, two affiliated colleges—Barnard College and Teachers College—and two affiliated seminaries—Jewish Theological Seminary (JTS) and Union Theological Seminary (UTS).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university's research efforts include the Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory, the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, and accelerator laboratories with Big Tech firms such as Amazon and IBM.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a founding member of the Association of American Universities and was the first school in the United States to grant the MD degree.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers and annually awards the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Discussions regarding the founding of a college in the Province of New York began as early as 1704.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Classes were initially held in July 1754 and were presided over by the college's first president, Samuel Johnson.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The college was officially founded on October 31, 1754, as King's College by royal charter of George II, making it the oldest institution of higher learning in the State of New York and the fifth oldest in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1763, Johnson was succeeded in the presidency by Myles Cooper, a graduate of The Queen's College, Oxford, and an ardent Tory.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the charged political climate of the American Revolution, his chief opponent in discussions at the college was an undergraduate of the class of 1777, Alexander Hamilton.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Irish anatomist, Samuel Clossy, was appointed professor of natural philosophy in October 1765 and later the college's first professor of anatomy in 1767.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Following the start of the American Revolutionary War and the arrival of Continental Army in 1776, the school suspended instruction for eight years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The suspension continued through the military occupation of New York City by British troops until their departure in 1783.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] During this time, the college's library was looted and its sole building requisitioned for use as a military hospital first by American and then British forces.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The legislature agreed to assist the college.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] On May 1, 1784, it passed "an Act for granting certain privileges to the College heretofore called King's College".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Act created a board of regents to oversee the resuscitation of King's College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In April of that same year, a new charter was adopted for the college granted the power to a separate board of 24 trustees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] For a period in the 1790s, with New York City as the federal and state capital and the country under successive Federalist governments, a revived Columbia operated under Federalists such as Hamilton and Jay.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] President George Washington and Vice President John Adams, in addition to both houses of Congress attended the college's commencement on May 6, 1789, as a tribute of honor to the alumni of the school who had been involved in the American Revolution.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1813, the college incorporated its medical school with The College of Physicians and Surgeons, a new school created by the Regents of New York, forming Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1857, the college moved from the King's College campus at Park Place to a primarily Gothic Revival campus on 49th Street and Madison Avenue, where it remained for the next forty years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] During the last half of the 19th century, under the presidency of Frederick A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Barnard, for whom Barnard College is named, the institution rapidly assumed the shape of a modern university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College was created in 1889 as a response to the university's refusal to accept women.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, university president Seth Low moved the campus from 49th Street to its present location, a more spacious campus in the developing neighborhood of Morningside Heights.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In March 1917, as a result of America's entrance into World War 1, Columbia president Nicholas Murray Butler formed the Columbia Reserve Officers Training Corps.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] All students over the age of 18 who passed a physical exam were entered into this program.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Within 4 months, over 1,400 students were enrolled within the program.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] They were one of 12 universities designated by the War department to create a naval section for the Student Army Training Corps.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] As part of this new program, the US Army charged Columbia to create a "War Issues" course.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, a similar course was created for Columbia students, a "peace issues" course that evolved into "Introduction to Contemporary Civilization in the West", part of the university's core curriculum for undergraduate students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, Columbia established a student application process characterized by *The New York Times* as "the first modern college application".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1928, Seth Low Junior College was established by Columbia University in order to mitigate the number of Jewish applicants to Columbia College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The college was closed in 1936 due to the adverse effects of the Great Depression and its students were subsequently taught at the Morningside Heights campus, although they did not belong to any college but to the university at large.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the 1940s, faculty members, including John R.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Dunning, Isidor Isaac Rabi, Enrico Fermi, and Polykarp Kusch, began what became the Manhattan Project, creating the first nuclear fission reactor in the Americas and researching gaseous diffusion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the aftermath of World War II, the discipline of international relations became a major scholarly focus of the university, and in response, the School of International and Public Affairs was founded in 1946, drawing upon the resources of the faculties of political science, economics, and history.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1947, University Extension, an evening school program open to all for a fee, was reorganized as an undergraduate college and designated the School of General Studies in response to the return of GIs after World War II.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Bicentennial was celebrated in 1954.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] During the 1960s, student activism reached a climax with protests in the spring of 1968, when hundreds of students occupied buildings on campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The incident forced the resignation of Columbia's president, Grayson Kirk, and the establishment of the University Senate.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Though several schools in the university had admitted women for years, Columbia College first admitted women in the fall of 1983, after a decade of failed negotiations with Barnard College, the all-female institution affiliated with the university, to merge the two schools.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College still remains affiliated with Columbia, and all Barnard graduates are issued diplomas signed by the presidents of Columbia University and Barnard College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] During the late 20th century, the university underwent significant academic, structural, and administrative changes as it developed into a major research university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] For much of the 19th century, the university consisted of decentralized and separate faculties specializing in Political Science, Philosophy, and Pure Science.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1979, these faculties were merged into the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1995, the Division of Special Programs, later called the School of Continuing Education and now the School of Professional Studies, was established to reprise the former role of University Extension.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger became Columbia's 19th president in June 2002, succeeding George Rupp.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger was appointed in October 2001 after arriving from the presidency of the University of Michigan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] His presidency emphasized campus expansion, defense of affirmative action in college admissions, support for government funding of private sector media, and opposition to disinformation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Under Bollinger's tenure, the university publicly launched a record $4 billion capital campaign in September 2006.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Financial aid was improved, eliminating loans for undergraduates from families earning under $50,000, and additional funds were allocated to support Bollinger's efforts toward the Manhattanville campus expansion, which nearly doubled Columbia's physical footprint.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] This expansion was supported by a major gift from trustee Gerry Lenfest.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Globalization efforts continued with the World Leaders Forum and the creation of the Committee on Global Thought, chaired by Joseph Stiglitz.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The 2008 financial crisis impacted Columbia's endowment.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The endowment recovered, hitting $8.2B in Oct 2013.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Despite the downturn, the university pressed on with Manhattanville construction, receiving final state approval in June 2009.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In May 2011, following the repeal of "Don't Ask, Don't Tell," the University Senate voted 51–17 to invite ROTC back after a 40-year absence, and Bollinger announced an agreement with the Navy.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has maintained its Global Centers network (Amman, Athens, Beijing, Mumbai, Paris, Nairobi, Istanbul, Santiago, Rio de Janeiro, Tunis, Tel Aviv), aiming to increase global engagement and international student enrollment.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] From 2014 to 2021, Columbia University pursued significant physical expansion, notably opening major facilities on the Manhattanville campus (ZMBBI, Lenfest Center, The Forum).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Key strategic initiatives launched included the Knight First Amendment Institute, Columbia World Projects, and the new Columbia Climate School (2020).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A $5 billion university capital campaign was launched (with a $1.5B A&S target), major gifts like $50M for A&S's Uris Hall renovation were secured, and the endowment grew significantly ($14.35B by mid-2021).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In February 2022, Columbia's mathematics professor Michael Thaddeus published a website and argued that data submitted by Columbia for U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] News college rankings was "inaccurate, dubious or highly misleading".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report* unranked Columbia citing failed verification.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In September 2022, Columbia acknowledged the submission of incorrect data to U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In June 2023, Columbia announced its non-participation in the rankings.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia offered to pay US$9 million to settle a class-action lawsuit by its students in Manhattan federal court over the alleged submission of false data to boost its U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In January 2023, Columbia University announced that Minouche Shafik would be the school's 20th president.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Previously, Shafik served as president of the London School of Economics and Political Science.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The federal government also launched an investigation into antisemitism and then withdrew funding, prompting the university to adopt new policies and adjust disciplinary processes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Claire Shipman was appointed acting president in March 2025.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also closed its Morningside Heights campus to the general public, allowing access only to holders of Columbia ID cards and approved guests.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia finalized a $220 million settlement to resume federal funding, agreeing to implement a set of reforms to address anti-semitism.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university also adopted the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In January 2026, the university announced that it had chosen Jennifer Mnookin, the chancellor of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, as the next president of Columbia, effective July 1, 2026.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In March 2026, a $481 million ruling that Columbia University had won against software company Gen Digital for infringing patents related to cybersecurity technology was overturned.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit stated that Columbia's patents may be invalid and sent the case back to Virginia federal court.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The majority of Columbia's graduate and undergraduate studies are conducted in the Upper Manhattan neighborhood of Morningside Heights on Seth Low's late-19th century vision of a university campus where all disciplines could be taught at one location.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The campus was designed along Beaux-Arts planning principles by the architects McKim, Mead & White.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's main campus occupies more than six city blocks, or 32 acres (13 ha), in Morningside Heights, New York City, a neighborhood that contains a number of academic institutions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university owns over 7,800 apartments in Morningside Heights, housing faculty, graduate students, and staff.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Almost two dozen undergraduate dormitories (purpose-built or converted) are located on campus or in Morningside Heights.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has an extensive tunnel system, more than a century old, with the oldest portions predating the present campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Some of these remain accessible to the public, while others have been cordoned off.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Butler Library is the largest in the Columbia University Libraries system and one of the largest buildings on the campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] It was completed in 1934 and renamed to Butler Library in 1946.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] As of 2020, Columbia's library system includes over 15.0 million volumes, making it the eighth largest library system and fifth largest collegiate library system in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Several buildings on the Morningside Heights campus are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Low Memorial Library, a National Historic Landmark and the centerpiece of the campus, is listed for its architectural significance.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Philosophy Hall is listed as the site of the invention of FM radio.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Also listed is Pupin Hall, another National Historic Landmark, which houses the physics and astronomy departments.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Here the first experiments on the fission of uranium were conducted by Enrico Fermi.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The uranium atom was split there ten days after the world's first atom-splitting in Copenhagen, Denmark.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Other buildings listed include Casa Italiana, the Delta Psi, Alpha Chapter building of St.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, Earl Hall, and the buildings of the affiliated Union Theological Seminary.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A statue by sculptor Daniel Chester French called *Alma Mater* is centered on the front steps of Low Memorial Library.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The statue represents a personification of the traditional image of the university as an *alma mater*, or "nourishing mother", draped in an academic gown and seated on a throne.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] She wears a laurel wreath on her head and holds in her right hand a scepter capped by a King's Crown, a traditional symbol of the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A book, representing learning, rests on her lap.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The arms of her throne end in lamps, representing "Sapientia et Doctrina", or "Wisdom and Learning"; on the back of the throne is embossed an image of the seal of the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] "The Steps", alternatively known as "Low Steps" or the "Urban Beach", are a popular meeting area for Columbia students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The term refers to the long series of granite steps leading from the lower part of campus (South Field) to its upper terrace.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, the university purchased more than two-thirds of a 17 acres (6.9 ha) site for a new campus in Manhattanville, an industrial neighborhood to the north of the Morningside Heights campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Stretching from 125th Street to 133rd Street, Columbia Manhattanville houses buildings for Columbia's Business School, School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia School of the Arts, and the Jerome L.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Greene Center for Mind, Brain, and Behavior, where research will occur on neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The $7 billion expansion plan included demolishing all buildings, except three that are historically significant (the Studebaker Building, Prentis Hall, and the Nash Building), eliminating the existing light industry and storage warehouses, and relocating tenants in 132 apartments.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Replacing these buildings created 6.8 million square feet (630,000 m2) of space for the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Community activist groups in West Harlem fought the expansion for reasons ranging from property protection and fair exchange for land, to residents' rights.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Subsequent public hearings drew neighborhood opposition.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] As of December 2008, the State of New York's Empire State Development Corporation approved use of eminent domain, which, through declaration of Manhattanville's "blighted" status, gives governmental bodies the right to appropriate private property for public use.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] On May 20, 2009, the New York State Public Authorities Control Board approved the Manhanttanville expansion plan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital is affiliated with the medical schools of both Columbia University and Cornell University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*'s "2020–21 Best Hospitals Honor Roll and Medical Specialties Rankings", it is ranked fourth overall and second among university hospitals.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's medical school has a strategic partnership with New York State Psychiatric Institute, and is affiliated with 19 other hospitals in the U.S. and four hospitals in other countries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Health-related schools are located at the Columbia University Medical Center, a 20-acre (8.1 ha) campus located in the neighborhood of Washington Heights, fifty blocks uptown.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Other teaching hospitals affiliated with Columbia through the NewYork-Presbyterian network include the Payne Whitney Clinic in Manhattan, and the Payne Whitney Westchester, a psychiatric institute located in White Plains, New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] On the northern tip of Manhattan island (in the neighborhood of Inwood), Columbia owns the 26-acre (11 ha) Baker Field, which includes the Lawrence A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Wien Stadium as well as facilities for field sports, outdoor track, and tennis.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] There is a third campus on the west bank of the Hudson River, the 157-acre (64 ha) Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and Earth Institute in Palisades, New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A fourth is the 60-acre (24 ha) Nevis Laboratories in Irvington, New York, for the study of particle and motion physics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A satellite site in Paris holds classes at Reid Hall.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 2006, the university established the Office of Environmental Stewardship to initiate, coordinate and implement programs to reduce the university's environmental footprint.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Green Building Council selected the university's Manhattanville plan for the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Neighborhood Design pilot program.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has been rated "B+" by the 2011 College Sustainability Report Card for its environmental and sustainability initiatives.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Kuchler U.S. potential natural vegetation types, Columbia University would have a dominant vegetation type of Appalachian Oak (*104*) with a dominant vegetation form of Eastern Hardwood Forest (*25*).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Transportation is the bus service of the university, operated by Academy Bus Lines.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The buses are open to all Columbia faculty, students, Dodge Fitness Center members, and anyone else who holds a Columbia ID card.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In addition, all TSC students can ride the buses.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the New York City Subway, the ("1" train) train serves the university at 116th Street-Columbia University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The M4, M104 and M60 buses stop on Broadway while the M11 stops on Amsterdam Avenue.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The main campus is primarily boxed off by the streets of Amsterdam Avenue, Broadway, 114th street, and 120th street, with some buildings, including Barnard College, located just outside the area.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The nearest major highway is the Henry Hudson Parkway (NY 9A) to the west of the campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] It is located 3.4 miles (5.5 km) south of the George Washington Bridge.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a racially diverse school, with approximately 52% of all students identifying themselves as persons of color.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Additionally, around 50% of all undergraduates received grants from Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The college is need-blind for domestic applicants.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, Columbia University announced a $400 million donation from media billionaire alumnus John Kluge to be used exclusively for undergraduate financial aid.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The donation is among the largest single gifts to higher education.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] However, this did not apply to international students, transfer students, visiting students, or students in the School of General Studies.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the fall of 2010, admission to Columbia's undergraduate colleges Columbia College and the Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science (also known as SEAS or Columbia Engineering) began accepting the Common Application.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The policy change made Columbia one of the last major academic institutions and the last Ivy League university to switch to the Common Application.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is an independent, privately supported, nonsectarian and not-for-profit institution of higher education.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Its official corporate name is Trustees of Columbia University in the City of New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Joint degree programs are available through Union Theological Seminary, the Jewish Theological Seminary of America, and the Juilliard School.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College and Barnard College are official faculties of the university; both colleges' presidents are deans under the university governance structure.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Senate includes faculty and student representatives from Teachers College and Barnard College who serve two-year terms; all senators are accorded full voting privileges regarding matters impacting the entire university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College is an affiliated, financially independent graduate school with their own board of trustees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Pursuant to an affiliation agreement, Columbia is given the authority to confer "degrees and diplomas" to the graduates of Teachers College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The degrees are signed by presidents of Teachers College and Columbia University in a manner analogous to the university's other graduate schools.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's General Studies school also has joint undergraduate programs available through University College London, Sciences Po, City University of Hong Kong, Trinity College Dublin, and the Juilliard School.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university also has several Columbia Global Centers, in Amman, Beijing, Istanbul, Mumbai, Nairobi, Paris, Rio de Janeiro, Santiago, and Tunis.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Select students can study at either the University of Oxford or the University of Cambridge for a year if approved by both Columbia and either Oxford or Cambridge.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also has a dual MA program with the Aga Khan University in London.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University was ranked 12th in the United States and tenth globally for 2023–2024 by *U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 2021, Columbia was ranked seventh in the world (sixth in the United States) by *Academic Ranking of World Universities*, sixth in the world by *U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*, 19th in the world by *QS World University Rankings*, and 11th globally by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] It was ranked in the first tier of American research universities, along with Harvard, MIT, and Stanford, in the 2019 report from the Center for Measuring University Performance.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 2025, Columbia was ranked 250 out of 257 top colleges in "Free Speech Rankings" by the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression and "College Pulse", after ranking 214 of 248 in 2024 and at the bottom of 203 in 2022/2023.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 2024 and 2025, Columbia received a D on the "Campus Antisemitism Report Card" of the Anti-Defamation League, which the advocacy organization first launched in spring 2024, in the lead-up to and in the context of campus conflict over the 2024 Columbia University pro-Palestinian campus occupations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has been the site of many scientific milestones, including the first nuclear fission in North America, the invention of FM radio and the laser, and key contributions to neuroscience.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Researchers at Columbia have also advanced efforts in technology, such as digital media, cellular imaging, and brain-computer interfaces.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia scientists have been credited with about 175 new inventions in the health sciences each year.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is affiliated with many research facilities, such as the Columbia Institute for Tele-Information dedicated to telecommunications and the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, which is an astronomical observatory affiliated with NASA.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a long-standing participant of the United States Department of Veterans Affairs Yellow Ribbon Program, allowing eligible veterans and their dependents to pursue a Columbia undergraduate degree regardless of socioeconomic status for over 70 years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Several prestigious awards are administered by Columbia University, most notably the Pulitzer Prize and the Bancroft Prize in history.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Other prizes, which are awarded by the Graduate School of Journalism, include the Alfred I. duPont–Columbia University Award, the National Magazine Awards, the Maria Moors Cabot Prizes, the John Chancellor Award, and the Lukas Prizes, which include the J.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Lukas Book Prize and Mark Lynton History Prize.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize, which is considered an important precursor to the Nobel Prize, 55 of its 117 recipients having gone on to win either a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine or Nobel Prize in Chemistry as of October 2024; the W.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Alden Spencer Award; the Vetlesen Prize, which is known as the Nobel Prize of geology; the Japan-U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Friendship Commission Prize for the Translation of Japanese Literature, the oldest such award; the Edwin Howard Armstrong award; the Calderone Prize in public health; and the Ditson Conductor's Award.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 2020, Columbia University's student population was 31,455 (8,842 students in undergraduate programs and 22,613 in postgraduate programs), with 45% of the student population identifying themselves as a minority.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Twenty-six percent of students at Columbia have family incomes below $60,000.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] 16% of students at Columbia receive Federal Pell Grants, which mostly go to students whose family incomes are below $40,000.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Seventeen percent of students are the first member of their family to attend a four-year college.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is home to many fraternities, sororities, and co-educational Greek organizations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Approximately 10–15% of undergraduate students are associated with Greek life.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Many Barnard women also join Columbia sororities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] There has been a Greek presence on campus since the establishment in 1836 of the Delta chapter of Alpha Delta Phi.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Daily Spectator* is the nation's second-oldest continuously operating daily student newspaper.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] *The Blue and White* is a monthly literary magazine established in 1890 that discusses campus life and local politics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] *Bwog*, originally an offshoot of *The Blue and White* but now fully independent, is an online campus news and entertainment source.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] *The Morningside Post* is a student-run multimedia news publication.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to numerous undergraduate academic publications.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Undergraduate Science Journal* prints original science research in its two annual publications.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Other publications include *The Columbian*, the undergraduate colleges' annually published yearbook; the *Gadfly*, a biannual journal of popular philosophy produced by undergraduates; and *Rhapsody in Blue*, an undergraduate urban studies magazine.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Professional journals published by academic departments include *Current Musicology* and *The Journal of Philosophy*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Graduate School of Journalism publishe*s The Bronx Beat* each spring, a bi-weekly newspaper covering the South Bronx.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In 1961, the journalism school founded the *Columbia Journalism Review*, a professional magazine which is published six times a year.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Defunct publications include the *Columbia University Forum*, a review of literature and cultural affairs for alumni.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to two pioneers in undergraduate campus radio broadcasting, WKCR-FM and CTV.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A student-run radio station, WKCR broadcasts to the Tri-state area and claims to be the oldest FM radio station in the world, owing to the university's affiliation with Edwin Howard Armstrong.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The station has its studios on the second floor of Alfred Lerner Hall on the Morningside campus with its main transmitter tower at 4 Times Square in Midtown Manhattan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Television (CTV) is the nation's second oldest student television station and the home of CTV News, a weekly live news program produced by undergraduate students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Philolexian Society is a literary and debating club founded in 1802, making it the oldest student group at Columbia, as well as the third oldest collegiate literary society in the country.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The society annually administers the Joyce Kilmer Memorial Bad Poetry Contest.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Parliamentary Debate Team competes in tournaments around the country as part of the American Parliamentary Debate Association, and hosts both high school and college tournaments on Columbia's campus, as well as public debates on issues affecting the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia International Relations Council and Association (CIRCA), oversees Columbia's Model United Nations activities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] CIRCA hosts college and high school Model UN conferences, hosts speakers influential in international politics to speak on campus, and trains students from underprivileged schools in New York in Model UN.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Many engineering entrepreneurs in New York City have attended Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Since 1990, graduates of Columbia have established more than 100 technology companies.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The student-run group Columbia University Organization of Rising Entrepreneurs (CORE) was founded in 1999 with an aim to foster entrepreneurship on campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Each year CORE hosts events, including #StartupColumbia, a conference and venture competition for $250,000, and Ignite@CU, a weekend for undergrads interested in design, engineering, and entrepreneurship.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Notable speakers include Peter Thiel, Jack Dorsey, Alexis Ohanian, Drew Houston, and Mark Cuban.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] CampusNetwork, an on-campus social networking site called Campus Network that preceded Facebook, was created and popularized by Columbia engineering student Adam Goldberg in 2003.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Mark Zuckerberg later asked Goldberg to join him in Palo Alto to work on Facebook, but Goldberg declined the offer.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science offers a minor in Technical Entrepreneurship through its Center for Technology, Innovation, and Community Engagement.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] SEAS' entrepreneurship activities focus on community building initiatives in New York and worldwide, made possible through partners such as Microsoft Corporation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg launched the NYC Media Lab to promote innovations in New York's media industry.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Situated at the New York University Tandon School of Engineering, the lab is a consortium of Columbia University, New York University, and New York City Economic Development Corporation acting to connect companies with universities in new technology research.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Lab is modeled after similar ones at MIT and Stanford, and was established with a $250,000 grant from the New York City Economic Development Corporation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Established in 2003 by university president Lee C.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger, the World Leaders Forum at Columbia University provides the opportunity for students and faculty to listen to world leaders in government, religion, industry, finance, and academia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Other speakers include President Yudhoyono of Indonesia, President Pervez Musharraf of the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, Iraq President Jalal Talabani, the 14th Dalai Lama, president of the Islamic Republic of Iran Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, financier George Soros, Mayor of New York City Michael R.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg, President Václav Klaus of the Czech Republic, President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner of Argentina, former Secretary-General of the United Nations Kofi Annan, and Al Gore.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Orchestra was founded by composer Edward MacDowell in 1896, and is the oldest continually operating university orchestra in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Undergraduate student composers at Columbia may choose to become involved with Columbia New Music, which sponsors concerts of music written by undergraduate students from all of Columbia's schools.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Notes and Keys, the oldest a cappella group at Columbia, was founded in 1909.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Queer Alliance is the central Columbia student organization that represents the bisexual, lesbian, gay, transgender, and questioning student population.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] It is the oldest gay student organization in the world, founded as the Student Homophile League in 1967 by students including lifelong activist Stephen Donaldson.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University campus military groups include the U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Military Veterans of Columbia University and Advocates for Columbia ROTC.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In the 2005–06 academic year, the Columbia Military Society, Columbia's student group for ROTC cadets and Marine officer candidates, was renamed the Hamilton Society for "students who aspire to serve their nation through the military in the tradition of Alexander Hamilton".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has several secret societies, including St.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, which was founded at the university in 1847, and two senior societies, the Nacoms and Sachems.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A member institution of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) in Division I FCS, Columbia fields varsity teams in 29 sports and is a member of the Ivy League.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The football Lions play home games at the 17,000-seat Robert K.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Baker Athletics Complex also includes facilities for baseball, softball, soccer, lacrosse, field hockey, tennis, track, and rowing, as well as the new Campbell Sports Center, which opened in January 2013.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The basketball, fencing, swimming & diving, volleyball, and wrestling programs are based at the Dodge Physical Fitness Center on the main campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Former students include Baseball Hall of Famers Lou Gehrig and Eddie Collins, football Hall of Famer Sid Luckman, Marcellus Wiley, and world champion women's weightlifter Karyn Marshall.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] On May 17, 1939, fledgling NBC broadcast a doubleheader between the Columbia Lions and the Princeton Tigers at Columbia's Baker Field, making it the first televised regular athletic event in history.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University participated in multiple firsts within collegiate athletics.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The football program is best known for its record of futility set during the 1980s: between 1983 and 1988, the team lost 44 games in a row, which is still the record for the NCAA Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The streak was broken on October 8, 1988, with a 16–13 victory over arch-rival Princeton University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] That was the Lions' first victory at Wien Stadium, which had been opened during the losing streak and was already four years old.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A new tradition has developed with the Liberty Cup.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Liberty Cup is awarded annually to the winner of the football game between Fordham and Columbia Universities, two of the only three NCAA Division I football teams in New York City.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Varsity Show is one of the oldest traditions at Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Founded in 1893 as a fundraiser for the university's fledgling athletic teams, the Varsity Show now draws together the entire Columbia undergraduate community for a series of performances every April.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Dedicated to producing a unique full-length musical that skewers and satirizes many dubious aspects of life at Columbia, the Varsity Show is written and performed exclusively by university undergraduates.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Various renowned playwrights, composers, authors, directors, and actors have contributed to the Varsity Show, either as writers or performers, while students at Columbia, including Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, Herman J.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Diamond, Herman Wouk, Greta Gerwig, and Kate McKinnon.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Notable past shows include *Fly With Me* (1920), *The* *Streets of New York* (1948), *The Sky's the Limit* (1954), and *Angels at Columbia* (1994).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] In particular, *Streets of New York*, after having been revived three times, opened off-Broadway in 1963 and was awarded a 1964 Drama Desk Award.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] *The Mischief Maker* (1903), written by Edgar Allan Woolf and Cassius Freeborn, premiered at Madison Square Garden in 1906 as *Mam'zelle Champagne*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The campus Tree Lighting ceremony was inaugurated in 1998.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] It celebrates the illumination of the medium-sized trees lining College Walk in front of Kent Hall and Hamilton Hall on the east end and Dodge Hall and Pulitzer Hall on the west, just before finals week in early December.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Students meet at the sundial for free hot chocolate, performances by *a cappella* groups, and speeches by the university president and a guest.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Immediately following the College Walk festivities is one of Columbia's older holiday traditions, the lighting of the Yule Log.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony dates to a period prior to the American Revolutionary War, but lapsed before being revived by President Nicholas Murray Butler in 1910.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] A troop of students dressed as Continental Army soldiers carry the eponymous log from the sundial to the lounge of John Jay Hall, where it is lit amid the singing of seasonal carols.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony is accompanied by a reading of *A Visit From St.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p01] Nicholas* by Clement Clarke Moore and *Yes, Virginia, There is a Santa Claus* by Francis Pharcellus Church.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] The university has graduated many notable alumni, including five Founding Fathers of the United States, an author of the United States Constitution and a member of the Committee of Five.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Three United States presidents have attended Columbia, as well as ten justices of the Supreme Court of the United States, including three chief justices.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] As of 2011, 125 Pulitzer Prize winners and 39 Oscar winners have attended Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty received multiple Nobel Prizes, including Joseph Stiglitz (Economics, 2001), Richard Axel and Linda Buck (Medicine, 2004), Edmund Phelps (Economics, 2006), and Orhan Pamuk (Literature, 2006), among others.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] In a 2016 ranking of universities worldwide with respect to living graduates who are billionaires, Columbia ranked second, after Harvard.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Presidents Theodore Roosevelt and Franklin Delano Roosevelt attended the law school.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Other political figures educated at Columbia include former U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] President Barack Obama, Associate Justice of the U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Supreme Court Ruth Bader Ginsburg,, William O.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Douglas, Supreme Court Justice and former Chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, former U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, former chairman of the U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Federal Reserve Bank Alan Greenspan, U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] One of the founding fathers of modern India and the prime architect of the Constitution of India, B.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Alumni of Columbia have occupied top positions in Wall Street and the rest of the business world.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Notable members of the Astor family attended Columbia, while other business graduates include investor Warren Buffett, former CEO of PBS and NBC Lawrence K.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Robson Walton, Bain Capital Co-Managing Partner, Jonathan Lavine, Thomson Reuters CEO Tom Glocer, New York Stock Exchange president Lynn Martin, and AllianceBernstein Chairman and CEO Lewis A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] CEOs of top Fortune 500 companies include James P.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Stevens of Lockheed Martin, Philippe Dauman of Viacom, Robert Bakish of Paramount Global, Ursula Burns of Xerox, Devin Wenig of EBay, Vikram Pandit of Citigroup, Ralph Izzo of Public Service Enterprise Group, Gail Koziara Boudreaux of Anthem, and Frank Blake of The Home Depot.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Labor organizer and women's educator Louise Leonard McLaren received her degree of Master of Arts from Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Many Columbia alumni have gone on to renowned careers in the arts, including composers Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, and Art Garfunkel; and painter Georgia O'Keeffe.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Five United States Poet Laureates received their degrees from Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia alumni have made an indelible mark in the field of American poetry and literature, with such people as Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg, pioneers of the Beat Generation; and Langston Hughes and Zora Neale Hurston, seminal figures in the Harlem Renaissance, all having attended the university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Other notable writers who attended Columbia include authors Isaac Asimov, J.D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Le Guin, Danielle Valore Evans, and Hunter S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] In architecture, William Lee Stoddart, a prolific architect of U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] University alumni have also been very prominent in the film industry, with 33 alumni and former students winning a combined 43 Academy Awards (as of 2011).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Some notable Columbia alumni that have gone on to work in film include directors Sidney Lumet (*12 Angry Men*) and Kathryn Bigelow (*The Hurt Locker*), screenwriters Howard Koch (*Casablanca*) and Joseph L.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Mankiewicz (*All About Eve*), and actors James Cagney, Ed Harris and Timothée Chalamet.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University's faculty has included many notable names in the role of university president, including 34th President of the United States Dwight D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Eisenhower, 4th Vice President of the United States George Clinton, Founding Father and U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Senator from Connecticut William Samuel Johnson, Nobel Peace Prize laureate Nicholas Murray Butler, and First Amendment scholar Lee Bollinger.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Other notable Columbia University faculty include Zbigniew Brzezinski, Sonia Sotomayor, Kimberlé Crenshaw, Lee Bollinger, Franz Boas, Margaret Mead, Edward Sapir, John Dewey, Charles A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] As of 2021, Columbia employs 4,381 faculty, including 70 members of the National Academy of Sciences, 178 members of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and 65 members of the National Academy of Medicine.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] In total, the Columbia faculty has included 52 Nobel laureates, 12 National Medal of Science recipients, and 32 National Academy of Engineering members.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University faculty played particularly important roles during World War II and the creation of the New Deal under President Franklin D.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Roosevelt, who attended Columbia Law School.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] The three core members of Roosevelt's Brain Trust: Adolf A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Berle, Raymond Moley, and Rexford Tugwell, were law professors at Columbia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Former United States Secretary of Labor, Francis Perkins was the principle architect of the New Deal and also earned her Master's from Columbia University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] The Statistical Research Group, which used statistics to analyze military problems during World War II, was composed of Columbia researchers and faculty including George Stigler and Milton Friedman.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty and researchers, including Enrico Fermi, Leo Szilard, Eugene T.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Pegram, Walter Zinn, Chien-Shiung Wu, Francis G.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Anderson, and Isidor Isaac Rabi, also played a significant role during the early phases of the Manhattan Project.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Following the rise of Nazi Germany, the exiled Institute for Social Research at Goethe University Frankfurt would affiliate itself with Columbia from 1934 to 1950.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] It was during this period that thinkers including Theodor W.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Adorno, Max Horkheimer, and Herbert Marcuse wrote and published some of the most seminal works of the Frankfurt School, including *Reason and Revolution*, *Dialectic of Enlightenment*, and *Eclipse of Reason*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Professors Edward Said, author of *Orientalism*, and Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak are generally considered as founders of the field of postcolonialism; other professors that have significantly contributed to the field include Hamid Dabashi, Rashid Khalidi, and Joseph Massad.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] The works of professors Kimberlé Crenshaw, Patricia J.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Williams, and Kendall Thomas were foundational to the field of critical race theory.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Columbia and its affiliated faculty have also made significant contributions to the study of religion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] The affiliated Union Theological Seminary is a center of liberal Christianity in the United States, having served as the birthplace of Black theology through the efforts of faculty including James H.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/columbia-university-p02] Cone and Cornel West, and Womanist theology, through the works of Katie Cannon, Emilie Townes, and Delores S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university is organized into eight undergraduate colleges and seven graduate divisions on its main Ithaca campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Each college and academic division has near autonomy in defining its respective admission standards and academic curriculum.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In addition to its primary campus in Ithaca, Cornell University administers three satellite campuses, including two in New York City, the medical school and Cornell Tech, and a branch of the medical school in Al Rayyan in Education City, Qatar.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is one of three private land-grant universities in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The main campus of Cornell University in Ithaca spans 745 acres (301 ha).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of October 2024, 64 Nobel laureates, 4 Turing Award winners, and 1 Fields Medalist have been affiliated with Cornell University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The institution counts more than 250,000 living alumni, which include 34 Marshall Scholars, 33 Rhodes Scholars, 29 Truman Scholars, 63 Olympic medalists, 10 current *Fortune* 500 CEOs, and 35 billionaires.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University was founded on April 27, 1865, by Ezra Cornell, an entrepreneur and New York State senator, and Andrew Dickson White, an educator and fellow state senator.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university was established as New York's land-grant institution following authorization by the New York State Legislature.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Ezra Cornell provided his farm in Ithaca, New York, as the initial campus site and contributed $500,000 as an initial endowment (equivalent to $13,074,000 in 2025).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] White agreed to serve as the university's first president.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] White oversaw the university's early development, including construction of its first two buildings, and traveled to recruit students and faculty.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university was formally inaugurated on October 7, 1868, with 412 male students enrolling the following day.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell developed as a technologically innovative institution, incorporating academic research into campus infrastructure and outreach.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1883, it became one of the first electrified universities, employing a water-powered dynamo to light parts of the campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Since 1894, the university has incorporated state-funded colleges that fulfill statutory requirements, and it administers research and extension programs jointly funded by New York State and the U.S. federal government.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1872, Cornell became one of the first U.S. universities to allow alumni-elected trustees on its board.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Cornell was home to literary societies that promoted writing, reading, and oratory.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Bureau of Education classified several of these societies as following the traditions of literary organizations at Eastern universities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1967, Cornell experienced a fire in the Residential Club dormitory that killed eight students and one professor.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In the late 1960s, Cornell was among the Ivy League universities that experienced heightened student activism related to cultural issues, civil rights, and opposition to U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1969, armed anti–Vietnam War protesters occupied Willard Straight Hall, an incident that led to a restructuring of university governance and forced the resignation of then-president James Alfred Perkins.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University and its academic programs have routinely ranked among the best in the world.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1995, the National Research Council ranked Cornell's Ph.D. programs sixth in the nation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The council ranked Cornell's College of Arts and Humanities faculty fifth in the nation, its mathematics and physical sciences faculty sixth, and its College of Engineering fifth.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2000, Cornell began expanding its international programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2004, the university opened Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar in Education City in Al Rayyan, Qatar.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2020, Cornell admitted that it had failed to disclose close to $1.9 billion dollars in Qatari funding, according to Section 117 of the Higher Education Act.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2026 it was reported that Cornell received $2.3 billion from Qatar, out of a total of $3 billion from foreign nations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university also developed partnerships with academic institutions in India, the China, and Singapore.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In August 2002, a graduate student group, At What Cost?, formed at Cornell to oppose a graduate student unionization drive run by CASE/UAW, an affiliate of the United Auto Workers.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The vote to unionize, held in October 2002, was rejected; At What Cost? was considered instrumental in the unusually large 90% turnout and the two-to-one defeat of the proposal, the first time a U.S. graduate school vote on unionization was defeated.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In March 2004, Cornell and Stanford University laid the cornerstone for the building and operation of the "Bridging the Rift Center," located on the border between Israel and Jordan, to be used for education.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Lehman, a former president of Cornell, described the university and its high international profile as a "transnational university".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In November 2025, Cornell agreed to pay $30 million to the federal government and invest $30 million in agricultural research in order to restore $250 million in funding and settle investigations into campus antisemitism and DEI practices.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University's main campus is located in Ithaca, New York, on East Hill, offering views of the city and Cayuga Lake.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The campus has expanded to approximately 745 acres (301 ha) since its founding, now including multiple academic buildings, laboratories, administrative facilities, athletic centers, auditoriums, museums, and residential areas.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2011, *Travel + Leisure* recognized Cornell's campus in Ithaca as one of the most beautiful in the United States, praising its unique blend of architectural styles, historic landmarks, and picturesque surroundings.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Ithaca campus is characterized by an irregular layout and a mix of architectural styles that developed over time through successive master plans.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] More ornate buildings generally predate World War II, while later construction reflects modernist and contemporary styles.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Several Cornell University buildings have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places: Andrew Dickson White House, Bailey Hall, Caldwell Hall, the Computing and Communications Center, Morrill Hall, Rice Hall, Fernow Hall, Wing Hall, Llenroc, and Deke House.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Morrill Hall has also been designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Three other listed historic buildings, the original Roberts Hall, East Roberts Hall, and Stone Hall, were demolished in the 1980s to make way for new campus buildings and development.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The majority of Cornell University's academic and administrative facilities are located on its main campus in Ithaca.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Architectural styles range from ornate Collegiate Gothic, Victorian, and Neoclassical buildings to more spare international and modernist structures.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Frederick Law Olmsted, designer of Central Park, proposed a "grand terrace" overlooking Cayuga Lake in one of the earliest plans for the development of the campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] North Campus is primarily residential, with ten residence halls for first- and second-year students and housing for transfer students in the Townhouse Community.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The West Campus House System showcases a blend of architectural styles, including Gothic-style buildings and residence halls collectively known as "the Gothics".
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In Collegetown, located near the campus in Ithaca, the architectural styles are diverse, reflecting the area's mixed-use nature.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Schwartz Center for the Performing Arts and two upper-level residence halls are surrounded by a variety of apartment buildings, eateries, and businesses.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University's main campus in Ithaca is located in the Finger Lakes region in upstate New York and features views of the city, Cayuga Lake, and surrounding valleys.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The campus is bordered by two gorges, Fall Creek Gorge and Cascadilla Gorge.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The gorges are popular swimming spots during warmer months, but their use is discouraged by the university and city code due to potential safety hazards.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Adjacent to the main campus, Cornell owns the 2,800 acres (1,100 ha) Cornell Botanic Gardens, which feature cultivated gardens, arboretum collections, and natural areas.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University has implemented several green initiatives designed to promote sustainability and reduce environmental impact, including a gas-fired combined heat and power facility, an on-campus hydroelectric plant, and a lake source cooling system.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2007, Cornell established a Center for a Sustainable Future.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The same year, following a multiyear, cross-campus discussion about energy and sustainability, Cornell's Atkinson Center for Sustainability was established, funded by an $80 million gift from alumnus David R.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Atkinson ('60) and his wife Patricia, the largest gift ever received by Cornell from an individual at the time.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] A subsequent $30 million commitment in 2021 will name a new building on campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2020, the university, which committed to achieving net carbon neutrality by 2035, operates six solar farms that provide 28 megawatts of power.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is developing an enhanced geothermal system, known as Earth Source Heating, designed to meet campus heating needs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2023, Cornell was the first university in the nation to commit to Kyoto Protocol emission reductions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The same year, a concert held at Barton Hall by Dead & Company raised $3.1 million for MusiCares and the Cornell 2030 Project, which contributed to establishing the Climate Solutions Fund to catalyze large-scale climate research across the university, administered by the Atkinson Center.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's medical campus in New York City, also called Weill Cornell, is on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] It is home to two Cornell divisions, Weill Cornell Medicine, the university's medical school, and Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Since 1927, Weill Cornell has been affiliated with NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital, one of the nation's largest hospitals.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] While Cornell's medical school maintains its own faculty and academic divisions, it shares administrative and teaching hospital functions with Columbia University Medical Center.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In addition to NewYork-Presbyterian, Cornell's teaching hospitals include the Payne Whitney Clinic in Manhattan and its Westchester Division in White Plains, New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Weill Cornell Medical College is affiliated with neighboring Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, Rockefeller University, and the Hospital for Special Surgery.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Many faculty members have joint appointments at these institutions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Weill Cornell, Rockefeller, and Memorial Sloan–Kettering offer the Tri-Institutional MD–PhD Program, which is available to selected entering Cornell medical students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] From 1942 to 1979, the Weill Cornell Medical campus also housed the Cornell School of Nursing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] On December 19, 2011, Cornell and Technion – Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa won a competition for rights to claim free city land and $100 million in subsidies to build an engineering campus in New York City.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The competition, established by former New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg, was designed to increase entrepreneurship and job growth in New York City's technology sector.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The winning bid consisted of a 2.1 million square foot state-of-the-art tech campus to be built on Roosevelt Island, on the site of the former Coler Specialty Hospital.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The following year, in fall 2012, instruction began at a temporary location in space donated by Google, at 111 Eighth Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2014, construction began on the Cornell Tech campus, and the first phase was completed in September 2017.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Thom Mayne of Morphosis Architects was selected to design Cornell Tech's first building.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In addition to the tech campus and medical center, Cornell maintains local offices in New York City for some of its service programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell Urban Scholars Program encourages students to pursue public service careers, arranging assignments with organizations working with New York City's poorest children, families, and communities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The College of Human Ecology and College of Agriculture and Life Sciences enable students to reach out to local communities by gardening and building with the Cornell Cooperative Extension.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Students in the School of Industrial and Labor Relations' Extension and Outreach Program make workplace expertise available to organizations, union members, policymakers, and working adults.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The College of Engineering's Operations Research Manhattan, located in the city's Financial District, brings together business optimization research and decision support services used in financial applications and public health logistics planning.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2015, the College of Architecture, Art, and Planning opened an 11,000 square foot, Gensler-designed facility at 26 Broadway in Manhattan's Financial District.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In September 2004, Cornell opened the Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar in Education City, near Doha, which is the first U.S. medical school established outside of the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The college, which is a joint initiative with the Qatar government, is part of Cornell's efforts to increase its international influence.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The college, a full four-year MD program, mirrors the medical school curriculum taught at Weill Cornell Medicine in New York City.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The college also offers a two-year undergraduate pre-medical program, which has a separate admissions process and was established as an undergraduate program in September 2002 as the first coeducational institute of higher education in Qatar.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The college is partially funded by the Qatar government through the Qatar Foundation, a Qatar state-led non-profit organization, which contributed $750 million for its construction.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The medical center is housed in a large two-story structure designed by Arata Isozaki, a Japanese architect.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2004, the Qatar Foundation announced the construction of a 350-bed specialty teaching hospital near the medical college in Education City, which was to be completed in a few years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University owns and operates a variety of off-campus research facilities and offers study abroad and scholarship programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's off-campus research facilities include Shoals Marine Laboratory, a seasonal marine field station on Appledore Island off the Maine–New Hampshire coast, which is operated in conjunction with the University of New Hampshire and focuses on undergraduate education and research.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Until 2011, Cornell operated Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico, which was the site of the world's largest single-dish radio telescope.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology in Ithaca conducts research on biological diversity in birds.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Additional research facilities include the Animal Science Teaching and Research Center, the Duck Research Laboratory, the Cornell Biological Field Station, the Freeville Organic Research Farm, the Homer C.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Thompson Vegetable Research Farm, and biodiversity laboratories in Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic and the Peruvian Amazon.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell offers various study abroad and scholarship programs that allow students to gain experience and earn credit toward their degrees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The "Capital Semester" program offers students the opportunity to intern in the New York State Legislature in Albany, the state capital.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell in Washington program enables students to spend a semester in Washington, D.C., participating in research or internships.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell in Rome program allows students to study architecture, urban studies, and the arts in Rome, Italy.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university is also a member of the Laidlaw Scholars program, which provides funding to undergraduates to conduct internationally focused research and foster leadership skills.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As New York state's land-grant university, Cornell operates a cooperative extension service, which includes 56 offices across the state.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] These offices provide programs in agriculture and food systems, children, youth and families, community and economic vitality, environment and natural resources, and nutrition and health.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university operates New York's Animal Health Diagnostic Center, which conducts animal disease control and husbandry.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell also operates eCornell, which provides online professional development and certificate programs and participates in New York's land-grant, sea-grant, and space-grant programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University was chartered by an act of the New York State Legislature (Chapter 585 of the Laws of 1865) which was later codified into Article 115 (sections 5701 through 5716) of the Education Law of the Consolidated Laws of New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University is governed by a 64-member board of trustees, which includes both privately and publicly appointed trustees appointed by the Governor of New York, alumni-elected trustees, faculty-elected trustees, student-elected trustees, and non-academic staff-elected trustees.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Governor, Temporary President of the Senate, Speaker of the Assembly, and president of the university serve in *ex officio* voting capacities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The board is responsible for electing a President to serve as the university's chief executive and educational officer.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] From 2014 to 2022, Robert Harrison served as chairman of the board.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Board of Trustees holds four regular meetings annually, which are subject to the New York State Open Meetings Law.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university charter (specifically, paragraph 1.b of section 5703 of the Education Law) provides that one member of the board, the life trustee, is the eldest living lineal descendant of Ezra Cornell.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2024, the current and longest-serving life trustee is Ezra Cornell, class of 1971, the great-great-great-grandson of the original Ezra Cornell.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] He celebrated 50 years of service as a board member in 2019.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] His eldest daughter Katy Cornell, class of 2001, is expected to become the next life trustee.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] On July 1, 2024, Michael Kotlikoff, who served as Cornell's 16th provost, began a two-year term as interim president, succeeding Martha E.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Pollack, Cornell's fourteenth president, who announced her retirement in May 2024.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's colleges and schools offer a wide range of undergraduate, graduate, and professional programs, including seven undergraduate colleges and seven schools offering graduate and professional programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] All academic departments at Cornell are affiliated with at least one college.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Several inter-school academic departments offer courses in more than one college.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Students pursuing graduate degrees in these schools are enrolled in Cornell University Graduate School.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The School of Continuing Education and Summer Sessions provides additional programs for college and high school students, professionals, and other adults.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's four statutory colleges include the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences, College of Human Ecology, School of Industrial and Labor Relations, and College of Veterinary Medicine.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In the 2010–2011 fiscal year, these four colleges received $131.9 million in State University of New York (SUNY) appropriations to support teaching, research, and service missions, making them accountable to SUNY trustees and state agencies.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] New York residents enrolled in these colleges qualify for discounted tuition; however, their academic activities are considered by New York state to be private and non-state entities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] They also do not offer discounted tuition for New York residents.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2023, among Cornell's 15,182 undergraduate students, 4,602 (30.3%) are affiliated with the College of Arts and Sciences, which is the largest college by enrollment, followed by 3,203 (21.1%) in Engineering, and 3,101 (20.4%) in Agriculture and Life Sciences.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The smallest of the seven undergraduate colleges is Architecture, Art, and Planning, with 503 (3.3%) students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Philanthropy has played a central role in Cornell University's growth, funding major academic programs, research initiatives, and campus development.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2024, the university's endowment stands at $10.7 billion, making it the 14th-largest among U.S. universities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2018, Cornell raised $743 million in private donations, ranking third behind Harvard University and Stanford University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Major single-donor contributions in recent decades have significantly shaped Cornell's professional schools.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 1998, Weill Cornell Medicine was renamed after a $100 million gift from Sanford I.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Weill, a 1955 alumnus and former Citibank CEO.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] By 2013, the Weills' total donations exceeded $600 million.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2017, Herbert Fisk Johnson III, an alumnus and chairman of S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Johnson & Son, donated $150 million to support the Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management, one of the largest gifts to a business school.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell Tech, the university's technology-focused graduate campus on Roosevelt Island, has received major philanthropic support.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2011, Chuck Feeney, a 1956 alumnus and founder of DFS Group, became Cornell's largest private donor, contributing $1 billion to fund the campus and other initiatives.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Jacobs, a 1956 alumnus and Qualcomm founder, and his wife, Joan, donated $133 million to establish the Jacobs Technion-Cornell Institute at Cornell Tech.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Other major gifts have supported research and sustainability efforts.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2010, David and Patricia Atkinson donated $80 million to establish the Atkinson Center for a Sustainable Future, funding research on environmental and sustainability challenges.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is a large and primarily residential research university, and a majority of its students are enrolled in undergraduate programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Since 1921, the university has been accredited by the Middle States Commission on Higher Education and its predecessor.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell operates on a 4–1–4 academic calendar, with the fall term beginning in late August and ending in early December, a three-week winter session in January, and the spring term beginning in late January and ending in early May.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is a land-, space-, and sea-grant university, and until 2014 was a sun-grant university as well.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Admission to Cornell University is highly competitive.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's undergraduate programs for the Class of 2028 received 65,612 applications, of which 5,516 (8.4%) were accepted.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] For enrolling first-year students, the middle-50% range for SAT evidence-based reading and writing was 730–770, while for mathematics it was 770–800; the middle-50% range for the ACT composite was 33–35.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university attracts a diverse student body.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2022, the proportion of admitted students who self-identify as underrepresented minorities increased to 34.2%, up from 33.7% in 2021, and 59.3% self-identify as students of color, up from 52.5% in 2017 and 57.2% in 2020.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Among the 5,168 admitted in 2022, 1,163 were first-generation college students, up from 844 in 2020.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university practices need-blind admission for U.S. applicants.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University, under Section 9 of its original charter, ensures equal access to education by admitting students without distinction based on rank, class, occupation, or locality.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The charter also mandates free instruction for one student from each Assembly district in New York State.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] From the 1950s to the 1980s, Cornell collaborated with other Ivy League institutions to establish a uniform financial aid system.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Although a 1989 consent decree ended this collaboration due to an antitrust investigation, all Ivy League schools still offer need-based financial aid without athletic scholarships.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In December 2010, Cornell pledged to match the grant component of financial aid offers from the seven other Ivy League schools and MIT and Stanford for accepted applicants considering these institutions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2008, Cornell introduced a financial aid initiative that incrementally replaced need-based loans with scholarships for undergraduate students from lower-income families.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Despite a 27% drop in the university's endowment in 2008, attributable partly to the 2008 financial crisis, Cornell president David J.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Skorton allocated additional funds to continue the initiative and sought to raise $125 million in donations for its support.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2010, Cornell met the full financial aid needs of 40% of full-time first-year students with financial need.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The average undergraduate student debt upon graduation, as of 2010, was $21,549.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell offers a wide range of undergraduate majors with an international focus, including African Studies, Asian-Pacific American Studies, French Studies, German Studies, Jewish Studies, Latino Studies, Near Eastern Studies, Romance Studies, and Russian Literature.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Students have the opportunity to study abroad on six continents through various programs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Asian Studies major, the Southeast Asia Program, and the China and Asia-Pacific Studies (CAPS) major provide opportunities for students and researchers focusing on Asia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell has an agreement with Peking University that allows CAPS students to spend a semester in Beijing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In the Middle East, Cornell's efforts are centered on biology and medicine.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar trains new doctors to improve health services in the region.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university is also involved in developing the Bridging the Rift Center, a “Library of Life,” a database of all living systems, on the Israel–Jordan border, in collaboration with those two countries and Stanford University.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell offers several joint degree programs with international universities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell has partnered with Queen's University in Ontario to offer a joint Executive MBA program, which affords its graduates MBA degrees from both universities.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell also offers an international consulting course in association with the Indian Institute of Management Bangalore.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University has been routinely ranked among the top academic institutions in the nation and world by independent ranking assessments.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2024, Cornell was ranked 10th in the U.S. and 12th in the world by *QS World University Rankings* and 20th in the world by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2023, the university was ranked 10th in the U.S. by *The Washington Monthly,* which factors research, community service, social mobility, and sustainability into its ratings.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In its annual edition of “America's Best Architecture & Design Schools,” the journal *Design Intelligence* ranked Cornell's Bachelor of Architecture program best in the nation for much of the 21st century, including from 2000 to 2002, 2005 to 2007, 2009 to 2013, and 2015 to 2016.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In its 2011 survey, the program ranked first and the Master of Architecture program ranked sixth nationally.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2017, *Design Intelligence* ranked Cornell's Master of Landscape Architecture program fourth in the nation and its Bachelor of Science in Landscape Architecture program fifth nationally.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Among business schools in the U.S., *Forbes* ranked the Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management ninth nationally in 2019.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2020, *The Washington Post* ranked the school eighth for salary potential, and *Poets & Quants* ranked it 13th nationally, fourth in the nation for investment banking, and sixth globally for salary.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management was ranked 11th nationally by *Bloomberg Businessweek* in 2019, and 11th nationally and 14th globally by *The Economist*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2013, the Johnson school was ranked second for sustainability by *Bloomberg Businessweek*.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's international relations program is ranked among the best in the world by *Foreign Policy* magazine's Inside the Ivory Tower survey, which ranked Cornell's undergraduate program 12th and its doctorate program 11th in 2012.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2015, Cornell was ranked third among New York colleges and universities for professor salaries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2020, Cornell University Library, with more than 10 million holdings, is the 13th-largest academic library in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] It was the first among U.S. colleges and universities to allow undergraduates to borrow books from its libraries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2006, The Princeton Review ranked it the 11th-best college library, and in 2009, it climbed to sixth.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University Press, established in 1869 but inactive from 1884 to 1930, was the first university publishing enterprise in the United States.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's academic units and student groups publish multiple scholarly journals, including at least five faculty-led and seven student-led publications.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University is classified among “R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity.” The National Science Foundation ranked Cornell 14th among U.S. universities for R&D expenditures in 2021, at $1.18 billion.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Department of Health and Human Services and the National Science Foundation are the primary federal sponsors, accounting for 49.6% and 24.4% of federal support, respectively.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is ranked fourth worldwide for producing graduates who pursue PhDs in engineering or natural sciences at American institutions and fifth for graduates pursuing PhDs in any field.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell has contributed to nuclear and high-energy physics, space exploration, automotive safety, and computing technology.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] It regularly ranks among top U.S. universities for patenting and startup formation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2004–05, Cornell filed 203 U.S. patent applications, completed 77 license agreements, and distributed more than $4.1 million in royalties to units and inventors; in 2009 it spent $671 million on science and engineering R&D, 16th nationally.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell has participated in uncrewed Mars missions since 1962 and played a leading role in the Mars Exploration Rover mission.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Its researchers helped discover the rings of Uranus and operated the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico until 2011, then home to the world's largest single-dish radio telescope.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Founded in 1952, the Automotive Crash Injury Research Center pioneered modern crash test research, including early cadaver studies that informed seat belts, energy-absorbing steering wheels, padded dashboards, and improved door locks.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell has also advanced parallel computing and research cyberinfrastructure.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In high-energy physics, Cornell built the second U.S. cyclotron in the 1930s, became the first to study synchrotron radiation in the 1950s, and operates the Cornell Electron Storage Ring beneath Alumni Field, once the world's highest-luminosity electron–positron collider.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Faculty including Hans Bethe contributed to the Manhattan Project.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell groups participate in the design of the proposed International Linear Collider, envisioned to complement the Large Hadron Collider and probe questions related to dark matter and extra dimensions.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Sage School of Philosophy was founded in 1891 with support from Henry W.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Sage in memory of Susan Linn Sage; that year it also launched *The Philosophical Review*, one of the first sustained U.S. journals devoted to philosophy.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Notable scholars have included Max Black, Edwin A.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Burtt, Norman Malcolm, John Rawls, George Holland Sabine, and Gregory Vlastos.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In a 2024 reputation ranking by the *Philosophical Gourmet*, the Sage School ranked 16th in the U.S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2024, faculty include Tad Brennan, John Doris, Rachana Kamtekar, Kate Manne, Julia Markovits, Andrei Marmor, Shaun Nichols, and Derk Pereboom.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2016–2017, Cornell had over 1,000 registered student organizations, spanning club and varsity sports, performing arts (including multiple a cappella groups), political and cultural groups, media, games, and outdoor clubs.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Cornell International Affairs Society fields a traveling Model UN team and hosts a large high school conference; the Cornell University Mock Trial Association regularly qualifies for national competition.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell United Religious Work coordinates programming across faith traditions; the Cornell Catholic Community is the largest single religious student organization.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Music groups include a symphony orchestra, concert bands, and choral ensembles, including the Glee Club and the Chordials.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Big Red Marching Band performs at athletic and campus events.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Founded in 1868, the Cornell University Glee Club is Cornell's oldest student organization.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell Outdoor Education and Outdoor Odyssey run outdoor courses and pre-orientation trips; the Cornell Astronomical Society hosts public observing nights at Fuertes Observatory.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university is home to Telluride House and three long-standing honor societies: Sphinx Head, Der Hexenkreis, and Quill and Dagger.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's student governments—the Student Assembly and the Graduate and Professional Student Assembly—collectively allocate about $3.0 million annually to support clubs and organizations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell hosts a large fraternity and sorority system with about 70 chapters; roughly 33% of men and 24% of women participate.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Zeta Psi was chartered during Cornell's first year.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Alpha Phi Alpha, the first intercollegiate fraternity established for African Americans, was founded at Cornell in 1906.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Alpha Zeta (1890) was the first Greek-letter organization founded in the U.S. for Latin Americans.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] La Unidad Latina, Lambda Upsilon Lambda (1982), later became the only Latino-based fraternity with chapters at all Ivy League institutions; Lambda Pi Chi (1988) was the first Latina-based (not Latina-exclusive) sorority founded at an Ivy League university.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Many Cornell chapters are among the oldest in their national organizations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Alpha Delta Phi chapter house (1877) is believed to be the first U.S. building constructed solely for fraternity use; the chapter's current home was designed by John Russell Pope.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Greek system reports substantial annual community service and philanthropy; serious conduct matters are handled by the university's judicial processes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Student-run newspapers include *The Cornell Daily Sun*, an independent daily, and *The Cornell Review*, a conservative biweekly.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Other outlets include *The Cornell Lunatic* (humor), the *Cornell Chronicle* (university paper of record), and *Kitsch Magazine*, co-published with Ithaca College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] *The Cornellian*, an independent organization, publishes the yearbook, which has received the Silver Crown Award for Journalism and the Benjamin Franklin Award for Print Design.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Students also operate WVBR-FM, an independent commercial FM station, and various internet streams.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's residential system comprises North Campus, West Campus, and Collegetown.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Coeducational housing began in 1971, and the university maintains a system of residential advisors.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] A 1997 initiative designated West Campus primarily for upper-level students and North Campus for first-years and some sophomores.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2022, the North Campus Residential Expansion added beds for about 800 sophomores.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] West Campus incorporates a residential college system developed through a $250 million project, influenced in part by Risley Residential College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Other options include Schuyler House (a former part of Sage Infirmary).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2025, The Princeton Review ranked Cornell's dining program fifth in the nation.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The university operates 29 dining facilities across campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] On North Campus, Morrison Dining and North Star Dining at Appel Commons serve as primary venues for first-year students.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Risley Residential College includes a historic dining hall modeled on the great hall at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell's 35 varsity intercollegiate teams compete in NCAA Division I as the Cornell Big Red, primarily in the Ivy League and the Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Teams frequently contend nationally in men's wrestling, men's lacrosse, men's ice hockey, and rowing.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As an Ivy member, Cornell does not award athletic scholarships.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Football claimed at least a share of the national championship four times before 1940 and has won three Ivy titles, most recently in 1990.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2010, men's basketball reached the NCAA “Sweet 16,” the first Ivy team to do so since 1979.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell runs one of the largest collegiate outdoor education programs in the U.S., serving over 20,000 people annually with more than 130 courses (e.g., backpacking, caving, climbing, sailing).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] COE also runs the student-led pre-orientation program Outdoor Odyssey.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Most COE classes are taught by paid student instructors and count toward the physical education requirement.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] The Lindseth Climbing Wall was renovated in 2016 to 8,000 sq ft of climbing surface (from 4,800 sq ft).
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornelliana refers to Cornell traditions, legends, and lore.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Traditions include Slope Day and Dragon Day, one of the oldest campus events (founded 1901 and usually held near St.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] First-year architecture students build and parade a dragon around central campus, followed by upper-class architecture students in costume; the historic bonfire has been discontinued due to environmental regulations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Campus lore includes myths about statues on the Arts Quad and a “kissing bridge” on North Campus.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Notable pranks include a 60-pound pumpkin and a disco ball mysteriously placed atop the 173-foot McGraw Tower spire; the tower is lit seasonally and plays music.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] School colors are carnelian and white; the unofficial mascot is a bear, dating to the live bear “Touchdown” introduced in 1915.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell provides professional and peer counseling services, and on-campus outpatient care through Cornell Health (formerly Gannett Health Services), with emergency and residential services provided by Cayuga Medical Center.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Historically, Cornell maintained residential infirmary care, including at the former Sage Infirmary.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell offers reproductive health and family-planning services and operates a student-run Emergency Medical Service (CUEMS) that responds on campus and provides training.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2009–10, six student deaths by gorge jumping drew national attention.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Temporary bridge fences were followed by installation of means-restriction nets on five bridges in 2013.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Prior to that cluster, Cornell's suicide rate had been similar to or below that of peer U.S. universities, including 2005–2008 when no suicides occurred.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell University Police are New York State peace officers with authority equivalent to municipal police in Ithaca.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] They provide 24/7 patrols, emergency response, crime prevention, investigations, and enforcement of state laws and campus regulations.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2024, Cornell had more than 250,000 living alumni, including 34 Marshall Scholars and 31 Rhodes Scholars.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Cornell is the only institution with four female alumni—Pearl S.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Buck, Barbara McClintock, Toni Morrison, and Claudia Goldin—who have won unshared Nobel Prizes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Alumni maintain ties through homecoming, *Cornell Magazine*, and the Cornell Club of New York.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] In 2015, Cornell ranked fifth among U.S. institutions for alumni gifts and bequests.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Representative alumni across fields include heads of state Lee Teng-hui, Tsai Ing-wen, Mario García Menocal, and Jamshid Amuzegar; U.S. officials Janet Reno and Ruth Bader Ginsburg; inventors Willis Carrier and Robert Moog; authors Thomas Pynchon and E.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] White; entertainers Bill Nye and Christopher Reeve; and sportspeople Pop Warner and Ken Dryden.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of October 2024, Cornell faculty members, researchers, and alumni included 62 Nobel laureates.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] As of 2023, Cornell had 1,637 full- and part-time professional faculty on the main campus, excluding those affiliated with Weill Cornell Medical College.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Notable current and former faculty include Hans Bethe, Frances Perkins, Charles Evans Hughes, Georgios Papanikolaou, Carl Sagan, M.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/cornell-university] Abrams, Vladimir Nabokov, Henry Louis Gates Jr., and Ray Wu.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In English, a ***curriculum vitae*** (English: / ... ˈviːtaɪ, -ˈwiːtaɪ, -ˈvaɪtiː/, Latin for "course of life"), commonly known as **CV**, is a short written summary of a person's career, qualifications, and education.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] This is the most common usage in British English.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In North America, the term *résumé* (also spelled *resume*) is used, referring to a short career summary, whereas CVs are much longer than resumes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] The term *curriculum vitae* and its abbreviation, CV, are also used especially in academia to refer to extensive or even complete summaries of a person's career, qualifications, and education, including publications and other information.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] This has caused the widespread misconception that it is incorrect to refer to short CVs as CVs in American English and that short CVs should be called résumés, but this is not supported by the usage recorded in American dictionaries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In many countries, a short CV is typically the first information that a potential employer receives from a job-seeker, and CVs are typically used to screen applicants, often followed by an interview.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] CVs may also be requested for applicants to postsecondary programs, scholarships, grants, and bursaries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In the 2010s it became popular for applicants to provide an electronic version of their CV to employers by email, through an employment website, or published on a job-oriented social-networking service such as LinkedIn.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In the United States, both a CV and resume represent experiences and skills and are used in application processes, but they serve different purposes.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] A CV presents a full history of academic accomplishments, while a resume provides a concise summary of qualifications.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] Both are tailored for specific positions, with CVs typically required for academic positions and resumes needed otherwise.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In the U.S., most employers use resumes for non-academic positions, which are one or two page summaries of experience, education, and skills.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] Employers rarely spend more than a few minutes reviewing a resume, so successful resumes are concise with enough white space to make them easy to scan.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] A CV, by contrast, is a longer synopsis of educational and academic background as well as teaching and research experience, publications, awards, presentations, honors, and additional details.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In general usage in all English-speaking countries, a CV is short (usually a maximum of two sides of A4 paper), and therefore contains only a summary of the job seeker's employment history, qualifications, education, and some personal information.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] A CV's format is not fixed: its main purpose to impress an employer, showcasing skills, experience and creativity.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] A short CV is often referred to as a résumé only in North America, where it is however also often called a CV outside academia.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] CVs are often tailored to change the emphasis of the information according to the particular position for which the job seeker is applying.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] A CV can also be extended to include an extra page for the jobseeker's publications if these are important for the job.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In academic and medical careers, a CV is usually a comprehensive document that provides extensive information on education, publications, and other achievements.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] Such a CV is generally used when applying for a position in academia, while shorter CVs (also called résumés in North America) are generally used when applying for a position in industry, non-profit organizations, and the public sector.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In recent years, there has been a move by research funding organizations, supported by the responsible research movement, towards the use of narrative academic CV formats, intended to add more emphasis to the societal relevance of a scientist's research, teaching, and outreach work.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] The term *curriculum vitae* can be loosely translated as '[the] course of [one's] life'.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] It is a loanword from Neo-Latin, which is why it was traditionally spelled *curriculum vitæ* using the ligature æ, also in English, but this is now rare.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/curriculum-vitae] In English, the plural of *curriculum* alone is often *curriculums* instead of the traditional Latin plural *curricula*, which is why both forms are recorded in English dictionaries.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The performing arts are excluded from these fellowships, but composers, film directors, and choreographers are still eligible to apply.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] While students are not qualified to apply, advanced professionals in mid-career, such as published authors, are encouraged to do so.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Upon receipt of the grant, Fellows are free to use the funds however they deem fit.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The goal of the grant is to provide recipients with dedicated time and freedom to pursue their projects or artistic endeavours, while being relieved of their regular duties.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Applicants are required to submit references as well as a CV and portfolio.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] As of 2025, the Guggenheim Memorial Foundation has funded over 19,000 Fellows with a total sum of almost $400 million since its inception.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Each year, the foundation receives a high number of applications; since its formation it has seen anywhere between 500 and 4,000 applications.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Out of these, approximately 175 Fellowships are awarded.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The size of each grant varies and the amount and duration of the grant is adjusted based on the individual needs of the recipients, taking into consideration their other resources and the purpose and scope of their plans.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The average grant awarded is between $40,000 and $55,000.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation is a private foundation formed in 1925 by Olga and Simon Guggenheim in memory of their son, who died on April 26, 1922.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] In 1924, Senator Guggenheim appointed Henry Allen Moe to oversee the creation of the foundation and to lead its first years.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The Foundation was officially chartered and incorporated by New York State and Governor Alfred E.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The organization awards Guggenheim Fellowships to professionals who have demonstrated exceptional ability by publishing a significant body of work in the fields of natural sciences, social sciences, humanities, and the creative arts, excluding the performing arts.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] In 2025, the Foundation announced their appointment of the 100th class of Guggenheim Fellows, including 198 individuals working across 53 disciplines.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] To commemorate the centennial year of the Foundation, a special exhibit, *The Guggenheim Fellowship at 100*, was mounted at the New York Historical Museum.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] The exhibit, opened August 29, 2025 to run through November 30, 2025, explores the rarely seen archives of the Foundation and highlights some of the most notable Guggenheim Fellows of the last century.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Since the inaugural class of 1925, over 19,000 fellowships have been awarded.
[src:guggenheim-fellowship/guggenheim-fellowship] Harvard University counts the most affiliated fellows at 176, followed by Yale University and Princeton University in 2nd and 3rd place, respectively.
